  "glossary": [
    {
      "term": "Camellia sinensis",
      "definition": "The plant species from which all true teas are made; an evergreen shrub native to East and Southeast Asia. Two primary botanical varieties: var. sinensis (small-leaf, cooler climate, complex-delicate flavour) and var. assamica (large-leaf, tropical, bold-malty flavour)."
    },
    {
      "term": "Tisane",
      "definition": "An infusion of any plant material other than Camellia sinensis — chamomile, peppermint, rooibos, etc. Colloquially called 'herbal tea' but technically not tea."
    },
    {
      "term": "Oxidation",
      "definition": "The chemical process by which polyphenol oxidase enzymes in the tea leaf react with oxygen, converting green catechins into brown theaflavins and thearubigins. The primary processing variable that differentiates tea types."
    },
    {
      "term": "Terroir",
      "definition": "The total influence of a growing environment on a crop's flavour — soil chemistry, altitude, rainfall, temperature range, cloud cover, and microclimate. Borrowed from French wine culture; equally applicable to tea."
    },
    {
      "term": "Camellia sinensis var. sinensis",
      "definition": "The original Chinese variety of the tea plant. Small, narrow leaves, tolerates cooler mountain climates, grows slowly, tends toward complex, sweet, floral flavour profiles. The basis of most Chinese and Japanese teas."
    },
    {
      "term": "Camellia sinensis var. assamica",
      "definition": "The Indian variety discovered growing wild in Assam in the 1820s. Large, broad leaves, thrives in warm and humid lowland conditions, grows vigorously, produces bold, malty, full-bodied teas. Dominant in Assam and Kenyan commercial production."
