      "contentBlocks": [
        {
          "blockId": "sec-history-block-01",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Let's start with a prediction. Look at the nearest shop that sells tea — a supermarket, a corner store, whatever is closest to you. The shelves almost certainly carry teas from China, India, Sri Lanka, and Kenya. That exact lineup — those four countries specifically — is not a coincidence. It is the fingerprint of roughly four centuries of trade, colonialism, and botanical theft. This section is the story of how that lineup came to be.\n\nBut we have to start much further back, in a forest in southwest China, with a story that may or may not be true."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-history-block-02",
          "type": "image",
          "url": "PLACEHOLDER",
          "altText": "IMAGE PLACEHOLDER: A hand-painted Chinese botanical illustration showing Camellia sinensis branches with leaves, buds, and white flowers, in the style of Tang or Song Dynasty nature painting."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-history-block-03",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE ORIGIN LEGEND\n\nAround 2737 BCE — or so the legend goes — the Chinese emperor Shennong was sitting beneath a tree when dried leaves fell into his pot of boiling water. The resulting infusion was pleasant. Shennong, who was something of a botanical experimenter, was intrigued. He called it 'cha.'\n\nNow, this story is almost certainly apocryphal. Shennong is a mythological figure, and the date is impossibly precise for something that probably evolved gradually over thousands of years. But the legend does capture something real: tea's earliest use in China was likely medicinal and accidental — a plant discovered by people paying close attention to what the natural world offered them.\n\nThe botanical reality behind the legend is Camellia sinensis — a small, glossy-leafed evergreen shrub native to the subtropical forests of what is now Yunnan province in southwest China, along with parts of Myanmar and northern India. This is the one plant. Every cup of genuine tea in the world — from a builder's mug of strong Assam in Manchester to a whisked bowl of matcha in Kyoto — traces its origins back to this shrub."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-history-block-04",
          "type": "image",
          "url": "PLACEHOLDER",
          "altText": "IMAGE PLACEHOLDER: Map of Asia with Yunnan province and the surrounding 'cradle of tea' region highlighted, showing the Mekong River headwaters and the border regions of China, Myanmar, and northern India where wild Camellia sinensis grows natively."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-history-block-05",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE CARTOGRAPHER'S LESSON\n\nHere is an analogy that might help you hold the geography in mind. Think about how mapmakers once worked: they mapped what they had directly explored, leaving the edges of the known world deliberately blank, marked 'terra incognita.' Tea's spread through history follows a similar pattern — it was known, mapped, consumed, and traded in China for over a thousand years while the rest of the world remained tea-blank. The map of tea culture in 900 CE would show a densely annotated China, a little spillover into Japan and Korea, and — everywhere else — blankness.\n\nHold that image. As this section progresses, watch the map fill in, and notice exactly what force filled each blank region: trade, colonialism, smuggling, war, and the economics of empire.\n\nTHE TANG DYNASTY: TEA BECOMES CULTURE (618–907 CE)\n\nThe earliest reliable written records of tea as a cultivated crop and cultural practice come from the Tang Dynasty. By the 8th century, tea had evolved from a regional medicinal drink into something closer to a cultural institution. And in 760 CE, a scholar named Lu Yu changed everything.\n\nLu Yu spent years travelling to tea gardens, talking to farmers, and documenting every aspect of tea cultivation, preparation, and appreciation. The result was the Chajing — the Tea Classic — the world's first book devoted entirely to tea. Lu Yu described not just how to prepare tea, but how to approach it: with attention, care, and a kind of respectful curiosity. He argued that making and drinking tea well was itself a form of personal cultivation.\n\nThe Chajing was a cultural landmark. It transformed tea from a plant you drank into a practice you performed. It also standardised a vocabulary and a set of values around tea that would influence Chinese, Japanese, and eventually global tea culture for the next thirteen centuries.\n\nBy the end of the Tang Dynasty, tea was so deeply embedded in Chinese culture that it had become a subject for taxation. Emperor Dezong introduced the first tea tax in 793 CE — and immediately created the world's first tea smuggling trade."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-history-block-06",
          "type": "image",
          "url": "PLACEHOLDER",
          "altText": "IMAGE PLACEHOLDER: A facsimile page or reproduction of the Chajing manuscript, showing classical Chinese calligraphy, with a caption identifying it as the world's first book on tea, written by Lu Yu c. 760 CE."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-history-block-07",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE SONG DYNASTY: TEA AS ART (960–1279 CE)\n\nIf the Tang Dynasty gave tea its cultural foundation, the Song Dynasty elevated it into an art form. Song-era tea culture is characterised by the development of whipped powdered tea — the direct ancestor of what we now call matcha — and elaborate tea-tasting competitions among the literati.\n\nSong tea was produced by steaming fresh leaves, pressing them into dense cakes, and then grinding them into a fine powder. To prepare a bowl, you whisked the powder into hot water until a thick, frothy layer formed on top. The quality of the froth — its colour, density, and how long it clung to the bowl — was a primary criterion of excellence. Emperor Huizong, one of China's most accomplished emperors and arguably its greatest art patron, wrote an entire treatise on tea and was said to spend hours each day on tea preparation.\n\nThis powdered tea culture reached Japan in the 12th century via Buddhist monks who brought seeds and preparation methods home from their studies in China. Japan preserved and developed it into what would eventually become Chado — the Japanese tea ceremony we'll explore in detail in Section 6. Meanwhile, China would move on: the Ming Dynasty (1368–1644) abolished the compressed-cake format, switched to loose-leaf steeping, and in doing so invented the brewing method that most of the world uses today."
