          "blockId": "sec-history-block-09",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE MING DYNASTY'S REVOLUTION (1368–1644)\n\nThe switch from compressed cakes to loose-leaf tea wasn't just a processing change — it was a cultural upheaval. The Hongwu Emperor of the Ming Dynasty, himself from a peasant background, found the elaborate court tea rituals decadent and abolished them. He mandated loose-leaf tea and simple steeping.\n\nThis change had enormous downstream consequences. Simpler preparation meant wider accessibility. Teapots replaced whisks and bowls. The Yixing teapot — made from the unique purple clay of Jiangsu province — became the vessel of choice, and a whole craft tradition developed around it. Different styles of teapot became associated with different teas. The gongfu approach to brewing — using small vessels, high leaf ratios, and multiple short infusions — emerged from this period.\n\nMore importantly for global history: loose-leaf tea was much easier to ship and trade than compressed cakes. The Ming Dynasty coincided exactly with the age of European exploration. The timing was not accidental."
