          "blockId": "sec-history-block-12",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE SMUGGLING EPIDEMIC AND THE COMMUTATION ACT\n\nTo make the British tea situation even more extraordinary: by the mid-18th century, more than half of all tea consumed in Britain was smuggled. Import taxes on tea were so crushing — reaching 119% at one point — that smuggling was not just common, it was the rational choice. Entire coastal towns had their economies structured around the tea-smuggling trade. The quality of smuggled tea was often appalling: dealers mixed genuine tea with anything similar-looking, including dried hedge clippings, to increase volume.\n\nIn 1784, Prime Minister William Pitt the Younger signed the Commutation Act, reducing tea import taxes dramatically to roughly 12.5%. Legal tea imports increased nearly tenfold almost overnight. The smuggling trade collapsed. Tea became affordable for ordinary British people for the first time — and consumption exploded. Within a decade, Britain had transformed from a coffee-drinking to a tea-drinking nation. Almost everything you associate with British tea culture — the omnipresent 'cuppa,' the builders' tea, the tea trolley at the office — traces its origin to this single piece of legislation."
