          "blockId": "sec-history-block-13",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "By the 1840s, Britain had a problem. The demand for tea was insatiable — by this point, the British were consuming 50 million pounds of tea per year. But all of it came from China, and the Chinese held every advantage: they knew the plants, the processing methods, and the cultivation techniques, and they weren't sharing.\n\nThe solution was Robert Fortune — a Scottish botanist working for the Royal Horticultural Society who had already travelled to China once and developed a useful skill: he could pass as Chinese at a distance, with the right clothing and a shaved head with a pigtail. In 1848, the British East India Company hired him to do something extraordinary: travel into the tea-growing regions of China, which were officially closed to foreigners, steal as many tea plants and seeds as possible, and bring them back along with the technical knowledge needed to cultivate and process them.\n\nFortune's mission, conducted over two clandestine journeys, was one of history's most consequential acts of industrial espionage. He collected approximately 20,000 tea plants and seedlings, packaged them in newly invented Wardian cases — sealed glass containers that functioned as portable greenhouses — and shipped them to the experimental tea gardens being established in Darjeeling and the Himalayan foothills.\n\nHe also recruited Chinese tea workers — people who actually knew how to process the leaf — and brought them to India to teach the technique.\n\nThe result: within twenty years, British India had a functioning tea industry. Within fifty years, Indian tea had largely displaced Chinese tea on the British market. The price of tea collapsed, making it affordable for working-class families for the first time. By 1900, the British Empire effectively controlled the global tea trade — not through Chinese imports, but through its own colonial plantations."
