          "blockId": "sec-history-block-15",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE COLONIAL PLANTATION SYSTEM AND ITS LEGACY\n\nThe establishment of tea plantations in India, Ceylon (now Sri Lanka), and later Kenya was not simply an agricultural project. It was a system of colonial labour extraction that depended on, in many cases, indentured workers brought from other parts of the empire.\n\nIn Assam, hundreds of thousands of workers were brought in under conditions that historians have described as close to bonded labour. The tea gardens required intensive hand-picking work during the harvest seasons — exactly the kind of labour that the 'two leaves and a bud' plucking standard demands. Workers lived in plantation 'lines,' tied to the estate and the employer by debt and contract.\n\nThis history is not separate from your cup of tea. The geography of global tea production visible today — the Darjeeling gardens in the foothills of the Himalayas, the Sri Lankan highlands, the great plains of Assam, the highlands of Kenya — was carved out of the colonial world by this system.\n\nIt is also worth noting that Sri Lanka's tea industry began not with tea but with coffee. Ceylon was a major coffee producer until the 1870s, when a fungal disease called coffee leaf rust destroyed the industry almost entirely. British plantation owners, needing a crop, switched to tea — and within a generation, Ceylon had become one of the world's leading tea producers. Ceylon tea, now Sri Lankan tea, was partly built on the ruins of a catastrophe.\n\nKENYA: THE MOST RECENT CHAPTER\n\nKenya's tea story is the most recent in our survey, and it connects directly to the colonial chain we've been tracing. British colonial agriculture established tea plantations in the Kenyan highlands in the early 20th century, primarily growing the assamica variety that produces the bold, brisk black teas ideal for blending. Kenya today is the world's largest exporter of black tea, ahead of India and China — a fact that would have been incomprehensible as recently as 1900.\n\nThe Kenyan story also has a human dimension we'll return to in Section 5: Indian labourers brought to East Africa to work on British colonial railway construction brought masala chai culture with them, which merged with local tea drinking customs to produce the distinctive Kenyan style of very milky, sweet spiced tea that remains the national drink today."
