          "blockId": "sec-history-block-16",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE TISANE DISTINCTION: A CRUCIAL CLARIFICATION\n\nBefore we close this section, we need to address something important that will affect every section that follows.\n\nYou will have noticed that everything we have discussed — the Tang Dynasty, the Opium Wars, the Boston Tea Party, Robert Fortune's espionage — concerns one species: Camellia sinensis. That is not an accident. It is definitional.\n\nWhen tea historians, trade documents, and serious tea drinkers say 'tea,' they mean an infusion made from Camellia sinensis. Everything else — chamomile, peppermint, rooibos, lemon balm, hibiscus — is technically a tisane. An infusion, an herbal drink, a botanical — but not tea.\n\nHere is an analogy: wine means fermented grape juice. Cider, mead, sake, and beer are all fermented beverages, but none of them is wine. Calling a chamomile infusion 'tea' is a linguistic convenience that obscures a meaningful botanical and historical distinction. The entire history of trade wars, colonial agriculture, smuggling networks, and diplomatic crises we have covered in this section concerns Camellia sinensis. Not a herb.\n\nThis distinction will matter in Section 3 when we classify the six tea types, all of which are made from Camellia sinensis. It matters now because it clarifies what 'tea history' actually is: the history of one remarkable plant and the world it remade.\n\nKEY TERMS FOR THIS SECTION\n\n• Camellia sinensis — the plant species from which all true tea is made\n• Tisane — an infusion of any plant other than Camellia sinensis; sometimes called herbal tea, but technically not tea\n• Chajing — the Tea Classic; the world's first book on tea, written by Lu Yu around 760 CE during the Tang Dynasty\n• Dutch East India Company (VOC) — the Dutch trading company that first brought tea commercially to Europe, around 1610\n• British East India Company — the British trading monopoly that dominated the China tea trade and later developed Indian plantation agriculture\n• Commutation Act (1784) — British legislation that dramatically reduced tea import taxes and collapsed the smuggling trade\n• Robert Fortune — Scottish botanist who conducted the 19th century's most consequential act of botanical espionage, transferring tea from China to British India\n• Wardian case — a sealed glass container used to transport living plants across long ocean voyages; the technology that made Fortune's tea heist possible"
