        {
          "blockId": "sec-botany-block-03",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "VARIETY ONE: CAMELLIA SINENSIS VAR. SINENSIS\n\nThis is the original. Native to the mountains of Yunnan, grown for millennia across China, Taiwan, Japan, and high-altitude gardens in India and Nepal. The sinensis variety is a compact, slow-growing shrub with small, narrow, leathery leaves. It is cold-tolerant — it can survive mild frosts that would kill assamica — which is why it thrives in mountain climates where winters bite.\n\nBecause it grows slowly, sinensis develops chemical complexity over a longer period. The compounds that produce delicate floral, grassy, honeyed, and umami flavour notes have more time to develop. The result is a leaf that, when processed correctly, tends toward nuance and complexity rather than power.\n\nSinensis is the base of virtually all Chinese teas (Longjing, Tie Guan Yin, Da Hong Pao, aged pu-erh), most Japanese teas (Sencha, Gyokuro, matcha), and the high-altitude teas of Taiwan and Darjeeling.\n\nVARIETY TWO: CAMELLIA SINENSIS VAR. ASSAMICA\n\nAssamica was discovered growing wild in the rainforests of Assam, in northeast India, in the 1820s — by British surveyors looking for exactly this kind of plant, under pressure from the East India Company to find a way to grow tea outside China.\n\nAssamica is a different beast entirely. It's a large, vigorous tree that can reach 30 metres in the wild. Under cultivation it's kept pruned to a harvestable bush, but its scale reveals its tropical origin: assamica evolved in a warm, humid, lowland environment with abundant rainfall and no frost. It grows fast. Its leaves are large, broad, and relatively thin compared to sinensis.\n\nThat fast growth and large leaf structure produce a leaf high in theaflavin precursors — the compounds that, when oxidised, create bold, brisk, malty flavours. Assamica is the engine behind Assam tea, most Kenyan and other East African teas, and many Sri Lankan teas. It is what makes breakfast blend tea punchy enough to stand up to a splash of cold milk.\n\nOne mnemonic worth keeping: Assamica = Assam = Ample, Assertive, Assamica. The A's stack up because the leaf itself is generous."
