        {
          "blockId": "sec-botany-block-05",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE COLONIAL BOTANY BEHIND THE VARIETIES\n\nHere is where the botany intersects with what you learned in Section 1. The discovery of assamica in Assam was not a botanical coincidence — it was a colonial discovery. British surveyors were looking for a locally growing tea plant because the East India Company was desperate to establish an Indian tea industry and break its dependence on China.\n\nWhen Robert Fortune later smuggled sinensis plants from China into British India, the plan was to plant them in Darjeeling and the Himalayan foothills — high-altitude, cool climates more suited to sinensis than to the lowland assamica. Assam, meanwhile, had its own plant: assamica flourished in the hot, wet lowlands and produced bolder, more volume-appropriate teas for mass commercial production.\n\nThis is why the sinensis/assamica split maps so neatly onto colonial agricultural history: Darjeeling (sinensis, mountain, nuanced) vs. Assam (assamica, lowland, bold) is not an accident. It is the botanical expression of two different colonial plantation strategies.\n\nKENYA AND THE ASSAMICA DOMINANCE\n\nKenya, as you'll remember from Section 1, entered the tea industry in the early 20th century under British colonial agriculture. The British planted assamica — the same variety used in Assam — because Kenya's highland climate, while elevated, is tropical enough to support it. Kenyan teas today are predominantly assamica, which is why they share the bold, brisk character of Assam teas and are staples of breakfast blends worldwide."
        }
