          "blockId": "sec-botany-block-06",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Now we get to one of the most important concepts in all of tea: terroir.\n\nThe word comes from French winemaking — it literally means 'land' or 'earth' — but it describes something much more complex: the complete set of environmental conditions in a specific growing location that collectively shape the flavour of the crop produced there. Winemakers have used the concept for centuries to explain why a Burgundy Pinot Noir from one side of a hill tastes different from one grown fifty metres away on the other side. Soil, microclimate, drainage, altitude, aspect toward the sun — all of these write their signature into the grape. The same is true, with equal force, for tea.\n\nFor tea, terroir has five major dimensions, and they interact with each other — which means you cannot evaluate them in isolation."
