          "blockId": "sec-botany-block-08",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE FIVE TERROIR FACTORS\n\n1. ALTITUDE\nHigher altitude means cooler average temperatures, greater diurnal temperature swings (hot days, cold nights), slower plant growth, and typically more cloud cover. All of these slow the rate at which the plant converts compounds, allowing flavour precursors to accumulate in the leaf. High-altitude teas tend to have more aromatic complexity, more pronounced floral notes, and a cleaner, more focused flavour profile.\n\nBut — and this is critical — altitude alone guarantees nothing. A high-altitude garden with poor soil, careless plucking, and inadequate processing will produce inferior tea. Altitude is one variable in a multivariate system.\n\n2. SOIL CHEMISTRY\nTea requires acidic soil, with an optimal pH between 4.5 and 6.0. Outside this range, the plant cannot efficiently absorb the nutrients it needs for full chemical development. Soil mineral composition also contributes directly to flavour: the specific combination of iron, manganese, magnesium, and other minerals in a given location is partly why teas from different regions taste different even when grown at similar altitudes.\n\n3. RAINFALL PATTERN\nTea needs significant rainfall — typically 1,500 to 2,500mm per year — but distribution matters as much as total volume. Tea grown during a dry period develops differently from tea grown with consistent moisture. The dry season before a first-flush harvest in Darjeeling concentrates compounds in the leaf. Too much water during the growing period can dilute flavour.\n\n4. TEMPERATURE RANGE AND DIURNAL SWING\nThe difference between daytime highs and nighttime lows matters considerably. In high-altitude gardens, cold nights slow the plant's respiration, reducing the conversion of complex aromatic compounds into simpler sugars. This preserves the volatile aromatic molecules that produce the floral, fruity, and muscatel notes characteristic of fine Darjeelings. Gardens with small diurnal swings — consistent warm temperatures day and night — tend to produce less aromatic but more body-forward teas.\n\n5. CLOUD COVER AND UV LIGHT\nThis factor becomes especially important when we reach shade-grown Japanese teas like Gyokuro in Section 4. UV light drives the conversion of the amino acid L-theanine into catechins (the tannin-like compounds that produce bitterness and astringency). More sunlight = more catechins, less L-theanine; less sunlight = less catechins, more L-theanine. L-theanine is the compound responsible for tea's characteristic umami flavour. High-altitude gardens often have natural cloud cover that partially replicates the effect of artificial shade."
