          "blockId": "sec-botany-block-10",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE TEA BELT: WHERE THE PLANT CAN GROW\n\nTea cannot grow just anywhere. The five terroir factors collectively mean that Camellia sinensis requires a very specific combination of conditions: acidic soil, significant rainfall, warm subtropical temperatures with no hard frosts (for most varieties), and good drainage. This combination exists only within a band roughly between 30°N and 30°S of the equator — what the tea world calls the Tea Belt.\n\nThe Tea Belt is why you don't see commercial tea production from Canada, Germany, Egypt, or Australia. It's not a lack of agricultural ambition — it's a climatic boundary that the plant imposes on itself.\n\nWithin the Tea Belt, the major producing regions each have a distinct terroir signature:\n\n• YUNNAN, CHINA: Ancient wild tea trees, red clay soils rich in iron, humid subtropical climate. Produces earthy, sweet, full-bodied teas including pu-erh. Home to Camellia sinensis's wild ancestors — some trees are over a thousand years old.\n\n• FUJIAN, CHINA: Coastal province, rocky and mineral-rich soils, varied altitude. Produces white teas (Bai Hao Yinzhen), rock oolongs (Wuyi Da Hong Pao), and jasmine-scented teas. The rock terroir (yancha) of the Wuyi mountains gives oolongs there a distinctive 'mineral' quality called 'rock rhyme.'\n\n• DARJEELING, INDIA: The Himalayan foothills at 600–2,100m altitude. A mix of sinensis and assamica-sinensis hybrids. First flush teas (March–April) are prized for extraordinary floral-muscatel aromatics produced by the cold winter followed by sudden spring warmth. Second flush (June) develops the full muscatel character. The altitude, diurnal temperature swings, and monsoon rain pattern create conditions impossible to fully replicate elsewhere.\n\n• ASSAM, INDIA: The Brahmaputra valley, hot and wet. Pure assamica country. The lowland climate and the variety together produce teas of exceptional body, malty richness, and brisk strength — the backbone of most commercial breakfast blends.\n\n• JAPAN (UJI, SHIZUOKA, KAGOSHIMA): All sinensis, all green tea (with the exception of some black tea production in Kagoshima). The steamed fixation method used in Japan, combined with volcanic soils and high humidity, produces the seaweed-vegetal-umami profile characteristic of Japanese greens. Uji, near Kyoto, is the historic heart of Japanese ceremonial tea.\n\n• SRI LANKA (CEYLON): Three altitude zones producing very different teas — lowland teas (bold, strong), midland teas (medium-bodied, bright), and highland teas (delicate, floral, with the famous 'Ceylon brightness'). As you'll remember from Section 1, Sri Lanka's tea industry was built on the ruins of the coffee leaf rust catastrophe of the 1870s.\n\n• KENYA: Assamica on the equatorial highlands at 1,500–2,700m. The combination of assamica boldness with high-altitude growing conditions produces teas with unusual brightness and briskness — described by professional tasters as 'the brightest black tea in the world.' Kenya is now the world's largest black tea exporter.\n\n• TAIWAN: Sinensis-dominant, focused almost exclusively on oolong production. The mountainous centre of the island (Ali Shan, Li Shan, Da Yu Ling) produces some of the world's most prized high-mountain oolongs — creamy, floral, and extraordinarily complex."
