          "blockId": "sec-botany-block-12",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "The tea plant grows continuously during the warm months, producing new shoots from the growing tips. Left unpruned, it would become a tree. Under cultivation, the plant is kept pruned into a flat-topped 'plucking table' — a shape that keeps all the growing tips at a uniform height and within arm's reach of a picker.\n\nPLUCKING STANDARDS: THE MOST IMPORTANT QUALITY DECISION IN THE GARDEN\n\nNot all parts of the plant are equal. The young shoots — the tender tip bud and the first two leaves below it — are chemically distinct from the older, tougher leaves further down the stem. The youngest tissue has:\n\n• Higher concentrations of L-theanine (umami, sweetness)\n• More abundant polyphenol precursors (future theaflavins and thearubigins in black teas; preserved catechins in green teas)\n• Higher density of aromatic compounds\n• Softer cell structure that responds better to rolling and processing\n\nThis is why the most widely adopted quality standard is 'two leaves and a bud' — the terminal bud plus exactly the two youngest leaves below it. This small package is the highest-quality part of the plant, and harvesting it exclusively is significantly more labour-intensive than grabbing larger handfuls.\n\nCoarser plucking — three to five leaves — includes progressively older tissue with lower compound concentration and tougher cell walls. The tea it produces is not necessarily bad, but it lacks the nuance and intensity possible from finer plucking. Commercial CTC production for mass-market tea bags typically uses coarser plucking because volume is prioritised over subtlety."
