          "blockId": "sec-botany-block-14",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE FLUSH SYSTEM: WHEN YOU PICK MATTERS\n\nIn seasonal climates, the tea plant goes through distinct growth periods, each producing leaves with a different chemical character. These periods are called flushes, and they matter especially in India, where the term is used most precisely.\n\nFIRST FLUSH — SPRING (approximately March–April in Darjeeling)\nThe tea plant has been dormant through the winter. The first growth of the new season carries compounds accumulated during the rest period. First flush Darjeeling teas are prized for their fresh, bright, intensely aromatic character — light-bodied, with green-golden liquor and a vivid floral quality. They are among the most eagerly anticipated teas in the world, released to market quickly after harvest.\n\nSECOND FLUSH — SUMMER (approximately June in Darjeeling)\nThe plant has been actively growing for months when the summer harvest arrives. Second flush Darjeeling develops the famous 'muscatel' character — a musky, grape-skin, dried-apricot quality unlike anything produced in other tea seasons anywhere in the world. The liquor is darker, the body fuller, the flavour more complex and lingering. Most connoisseurs consider second flush Darjeeling to represent the tea at its peak.\n\nMONSOON FLUSH (approximately July–September)\nHeavy rainfall dilutes the compound concentration in the leaf. Monsoon teas tend to be lower in price and quality — larger volume, less complex — and are used primarily in commercial blends rather than single-origin teas.\n\nAUTUMNAL FLUSH (approximately October–November)\nThe last harvest before winter dormancy. Autumnal teas have a distinctly different character: heavier, woodier, and earthier than either flush tea. They lack the brightness of first flush or the muscatel intensity of second flush, but have their own character — and often considerable depth.\n\nIn China and Japan, harvest seasons are less formally named but equally important. Japanese shincha ('new tea') — the first harvest of the year, typically in late April or early May — is treated with similar reverence to Darjeeling first flush, and is consumed fresh and young rather than stored.\n\nLEAF GRADES: WHAT THEY DO AND DO NOT TELL YOU\n\nYou will encounter leaf grades on tea packaging: OP (Orange Pekoe), FOP (Flowery Orange Pekoe), GFOP, TGFOP, FTGFOP. These are grading systems that describe the size and style of the processed leaf, not the quality or flavour of the tea.\n\nOrange Pekoe describes whole, unbroken tea leaves. The 'orange' has nothing to do with citrus flavour — it most likely refers to the Dutch House of Orange, through whose traders the grading system originally passed, or to the golden-orange colour of the growing bud tip.\n\nFOP (Flowery Orange Pekoe) includes more bud tips; TGFOP (Tippy Golden Flowery Orange Pekoe) describes a leaf with a high proportion of golden-coloured dried bud tips. More tips generally indicate finer plucking and a higher-quality picking standard — but the grade still tells you nothing about the terroir, the harvest season, the processing quality, or the cup character.\n\nKEY TERMS FOR THIS SECTION\n\n• Camellia sinensis var. sinensis — small-leaf, cool-climate, slow-growing variety; complex, nuanced flavour; basis of most Chinese and Japanese teas\n• Camellia sinensis var. assamica — large-leaf, tropical, fast-growing variety; bold, malty flavour; dominant in Assam, Kenya, and Sri Lanka\n• Terroir — the complete set of environmental conditions (altitude, soil, rainfall, temperature, UV/cloud) that collectively shape the flavour of a crop\n• Tea Belt — the band of tea-producing countries roughly between 30°N and 30°S latitude\n• Plucking table — the flat-topped, pruned shape maintained in cultivated tea gardens\n• Two leaves and a bud — the standard plucking method for quality teas; the terminal bud plus the two youngest leaves\n• Flush — a distinct harvest period within the growing season; in Darjeeling: first flush (spring), second flush (summer), monsoon flush, autumnal flush\n• Muscatel — the distinctive musky, apricot-stone flavour character of Darjeeling second flush teas\n• Orange Pekoe (OP) — a leaf grade describing whole, unbroken tea leaves; not a flavour descriptor or tea type\n• L-theanine — the amino acid in tea responsible for umami flavour and focus; highest in young tissue and shade-grown leaves\n• Diurnal swing — the temperature difference between daytime highs and nighttime lows; higher swings typically produce more aromatic teas at altitude"
