        {
          "blockId": "sec-types-block-01",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Let's start with the single most important fact in all of tea, the one that changes how everything else makes sense:\n\nAll six major types of tea — white, green, yellow, oolong, black, and pu-erh — are made from the same plant. Camellia sinensis. Not six plants. One plant.\n\nThe differences between a pale, honeyed white tea and a dark, earthy pu-erh aged for twenty years are not botanical. They are not about where the plant grew or what variety it is, though both of those matter to the final flavour profile. They are entirely about what the tea maker did with the leaf in the hours and days after it was picked.\n\nHere is the analogy that makes this click:\n\nA PHOTOGRAPHER'S DARKROOM\n\nImagine a film photographer who shoots the same subject — say, a street market at dusk — on the same roll of film. In the darkroom, they have three different chemical development processes available. Process A produces a vivid, high-contrast image with sharp colours. Process B produces a muted, warm, sepia-toned print. Process C produces a long-exposure ghost image, blurred and atmospheric.\n\nThe subject hasn't changed. The film hasn't changed. What changed is the process applied after the photograph was taken. And the process created something so different that a viewer, shown the three prints without context, might not believe they came from the same roll of film.\n\nThis is exactly what happens with tea. The leaf is the film. The tea maker's processing decisions are the darkroom chemistry. Six different processes produce six completely different teas from the same morning's harvest.\n\nWhat makes this more than just an interesting fact is that it has a practical consequence: once you understand processing, you can reason about any unfamiliar tea from first principles. You don't need to memorise a lookup table of tea types. You can read a processing description or a few tasting notes and work out where in the six-type spectrum a tea sits — and what it will taste like."
