        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-types-block-03",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE ENZYME AT THE CENTRE OF EVERYTHING: POLYPHENOL OXIDASE\n\nTo understand why processing creates such different outcomes, you need to know about one enzyme. In Section 2, you learned that tea leaves contain polyphenols — catechins and related compounds — that contribute to flavour, astringency, and potential health benefits. What you didn't yet know is that the leaf also contains an enzyme called polyphenol oxidase (PPO).\n\nWhen a tea leaf is damaged — by rolling, bruising, or crushing — the cell walls break, and polyphenol oxidase comes into contact with catechins and atmospheric oxygen. A chemical reaction begins: catechins are progressively converted into new compounds called theaflavins (bright golden-orange) and thearubigins (deep amber-brown). This process is what we call oxidation, and it is the master variable that distinguishes virtually all six tea types from one another.\n\nHere is what oxidation does to the leaf:\n• The colour of the leaf changes from green to brown\n• The flavour shifts from fresh, vegetal, and grassy toward rich, malty, and full-bodied\n• Catechins (the bitter, astringent, antioxidant compounds) decrease\n• Theaflavins and thearubigins (the compounds that create briskness, brightness, and body in black tea) increase\n• Aroma profiles change dramatically — fresh green aromas give way to fruity, floral, and finally malty notes as oxidation progresses\n\nThe tea maker's most consequential single decision is: when do I stop oxidation? They stop it by applying heat — a step called fixation — which denatures the polyphenol oxidase enzyme and locks the leaf at whatever stage of oxidation it has reached.\n\n• Stop immediately (green and yellow teas): the leaf retains its green colour and catechin-rich, fresh, vegetal character\n• Allow partial oxidation before fixing (oolongs): the leaf develops floral, fruity, and toasty notes while retaining some catechin freshness\n• Allow full oxidation before fixing (black teas): the leaf turns brown and develops the full malty, brisk character of the theaflavins and thearubigins\n• Skip conventional fixation and allow ageing or microbial fermentation (pu-erh): an entirely different transformation unfolds over months or years\n\nThis is the key: fixation timing IS the tea type. Everything else — withering, rolling, firing — is in service of enabling and controlling the degree of oxidation."
