          "blockId": "sec-types-block-05",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE PROCESSING SEQUENCE\n\nBefore we profile each of the six types, it helps to understand the individual processing steps and what each one does. Think of these as tools in a toolkit — the tea maker selects which tools to use, in what order, and for how long, to steer the leaf toward the intended result.\n\nSTEP 1: WITHERING\nImmediately after picking, freshly harvested leaves are spread out on bamboo trays or in large withering troughs and allowed to lose moisture — typically 20–30% of their water content — over 12–24 hours (or shorter, in some methods). Withering softens the leaf, making it pliable enough for rolling without shattering. It also initiates very gentle enzymatic activity and concentrates flavour compounds. For most black teas, a long, thorough wither is important. For green teas, withering may be brief or skipped entirely in some Japanese methods.\n\nSTEP 2: FIXATION (SHA QING — 'KILL-GREEN')\nThis is the heat step that halts oxidation. By applying sufficient heat, the tea maker denatures polyphenol oxidase, locking the leaf at whatever oxidation stage it has reached. There are two major methods:\n\n• PAN-FIRING (Chinese method): Leaves are tumbled in a hot wok or rotating drum at 250–300°C for a few minutes. This creates a slightly charred or toasty note in the finished tea — the characteristic chestnut or roasted quality of many Chinese green teas. The rolling motion simultaneously begins shaping the leaf.\n\n• STEAMING (Japanese method): Leaves are briefly blasted with steam at around 100°C for 15–40 seconds (or longer for fukamushi 'deep-steamed' styles). This fixes the leaf faster than pan-firing and results in a brighter green colour, more pronounced vegetal, seaweed, and umami notes, and a silkier mouthfeel. Japanese Senchas, Gyokuros, and matcha all use this method.\n\nSTEP 3: ROLLING AND SHAPING\nRolling and shaping serve multiple functions: they break the cell walls (which is what allows oxidation in black and oolong teas), they shape the leaf into its characteristic form (twisted, rolled into balls, flat-pressed, needle-shaped), and they concentrate volatile aromatics on the surface of the leaf. Rolling technique varies enormously by tea style. Heavily rolled ball-form oolongs (like Taiwanese Ali Shan) are rolled repeatedly over many hours. Flat-pressed teas like Longjing are pressed against the pan wall.\n\nSTEP 4: OXIDATION (for teas that use it)\nIn teas where oxidation is desired, the rolled leaf is spread out in a climate-controlled environment — typically cool and humid — and left to oxidise for a controlled period. Tea makers monitor the colour change (green → copper → brown) and the aroma development. For oolong, the maker is aiming for a specific window in this transformation. For black tea, they let the process run to near-completion.\n\nSTEP 5: FIRING / DRYING\nThe final heat step removes remaining moisture, halts any residual enzymatic activity, and sets the final flavour profile. The temperature and duration of the firing affect character significantly: a higher firing temperature produces more roasted, toasty notes; a lower, longer firing produces a cleaner, more delicate result. Some teas are fired multiple times to achieve specific flavour profiles (roasted oolongs, for example, undergo repeated high-temperature firings that fundamentally transform their character).\n\nOPTIONAL STEP: MEN HUAN (for yellow tea only)\nUnique to yellow tea: after fixation, the leaf is lightly wrapped in paper or cloth while still warm and slightly damp, and left to rest in this wrapped state for several hours. During this smothering step, residual heat and moisture create a mild, non-enzymatic chemical transformation that softens the grassiness of a green tea and produces yellow tea's characteristic mellow, smooth, slightly sweet profile. The leaf slowly turns a yellowish-green.\n\nOPTIONAL STEP: AGEING AND FERMENTATION (for pu-erh)\nPu-erh undergoes a transformation that goes far beyond standard tea processing. The leaf is first processed into a raw base called mao cha — essentially a green tea form — and then either pressed into cakes for natural long-term ageing (sheng/raw pu-erh) or subjected to a controlled wet-piling process (shou/ripe pu-erh) in which microorganisms — specifically fungi and bacteria — transform the leaf chemistry over 45–60 days, mimicking decades of natural ageing. Both paths produce earthy, smooth, complex teas that are categorically different from any other tea type."
        },
