          "blockId": "sec-types-block-07",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "THE SIX TEA TYPES: PROFILES\n\nWith the processing toolkit understood, the six types make logical sense rather than requiring memorisation.\n\n────────────────────────────────────────\nTYPE 1: WHITE TEA\n────────────────────────────────────────\nOxidation level: 0–15% (minimal, natural)\nKey processing: Sun-withering or low-heat air-drying only. No rolling. No fixation step. The leaf is simply allowed to wither slowly, losing moisture over days, with minimal handling.\n\nWhat this produces: Because the leaf is barely disturbed, polyphenol oxidase is only minimally activated. The tea retains the delicate, fresh, slightly honeyed character of the youngest tissue — particularly when made from buds (Silver Needle / Bai Hao Yinzhen) or young leaves (White Peony / Bai Mudan).\n\nFlavour profile: Pale golden liquor. Delicate, clean, and slightly sweet. Floral and honeyed top notes. Gentle, soft body with minimal astringency. Sometimes a subtle hay or dried flower quality from the withering process.\n\nTypical origins: Fujian province, China (Fuding and Zhenghe counties for the finest). Darjeeling (increasingly). Some Sri Lankan estates.\n\nKey examples: Bai Hao Yinzhen (Silver Needle) — entirely bud tips, the most prized white tea. Bai Mudan (White Peony) — bud plus one or two young leaves, more body.\n\nA NOTE ON THE 'NATURAL OXIDATION' QUESTION: Some white teas do undergo a small amount of slow oxidation during the extended wither — which is why they are not classified as 0% oxidised but 0–15%. This is slow, passive, and uncontrolled, very different from the deliberate rolling-and-oxidising of an oolong or black tea.\n\n────────────────────────────────────────\nTYPE 2: GREEN TEA\n────────────────────────────────────────\nOxidation level: 0% (none — fixed immediately)\nKey processing: Brief wither (or none) → immediate fixation (pan-firing or steaming) → rolling/shaping → drying. The defining decision is early, swift fixation that stops PPO before any oxidation can begin.\n\nWhat this produces: All the original catechins are retained. The leaf preserves its green colour and the full spectrum of fresh, grassy, vegetal, and umami compounds that would be converted by oxidation.\n\nFlavour profile: Pale green to golden-yellow liquor. Fresh and vegetal. Chinese greens (pan-fired): toasty, chestnut, nutty. Japanese greens (steamed): grassy, umami-rich, seaweed, spinach. High-quality Japanese greens (shade-grown Gyokuro): extraordinarily sweet and umami-forward with minimal bitterness.\n\nTypical origins: China (Longjing/Dragon Well from Hangzhou, Bi Luo Chun from Suzhou, Huangshan Maofeng from Anhui). Japan (Sencha, Gyokuro, Bancha, matcha, hojicha — all green in base, though hojicha is roasted post-process).\n\nKey examples: Longjing (Dragon Well) — flat, sword-shaped leaves, toasty and sweet. Sencha — needle-shaped, Japan's everyday tea, fresh and vegetal. Gyokuro — shade-grown, extraordinary umami richness. Matcha — stone-ground powder, the base of Japanese tea ceremony.\n\n────────────────────────────────────────\nTYPE 3: YELLOW TEA\n────────────────────────────────────────\nOxidation level: 0–10% (minimal, non-enzymatic transformation)\nKey processing: Similar to green tea — fixation, light rolling — but with the addition of the men huan (smothering) step, in which the fixed leaf is wrapped while warm and damp and allowed to undergo a slow, mellow transformation.\n\nWhat this produces: Yellow tea occupies the space between green and white tea. It lacks the grassiness of some green teas, having been mellowed by the smothering process, but retains their freshness. The resulting tea is exceptionally smooth, mellow, and approachable.\n\nFlavour profile: Pale yellow to light gold liquor. Mellow, smooth, and soft. Less vegetal than green tea. A gentle sweetness and floral note. The easiest of the six types to drink without any astringency at all.\n\nTypical origins: Almost exclusively produced in China (Hunan province: Junshan Yinzhen; Sichuan province: Mengding Huangya; Anhui province: Huoshan Huangya). Yellow tea is extremely rare and very little is exported — many tea drinkers never encounter it.\n\nKey examples: Junshan Yinzhen (Golden Needles from Junshan Island, Lake Dongting) — often cited as China's most exquisite yellow tea.\n\nA NOTE ON RARITY: Yellow tea's labour-intensive men huan process, combined with low consumer awareness outside China, makes it economically marginal. Production has declined significantly over the past century. Some tea scholars argue it is at risk of being lost.\n\n────────────────────────────────────────\nTYPE 4: OOLONG TEA\n────────────────────────────────────────\nOxidation level: 15–85% (the vast middle ground)\nKey processing: Wither → partial cell damage (bruising or tossing) → partial oxidation → fixation at a specific point in the oxidation window → rolling → drying and often repeated roasting.\n\nWhat this produces: Oolong is not one flavour profile — it is a spectrum. At the light end (15–30% oxidation), you get jade oolongs: fresh, floral, intensely aromatic, with a creamy mouthfeel and orchid or lily-of-the-valley notes. At the dark end (60–85% oxidation), you get heavily roasted oolongs: deep amber, toasty, caramelised, with dried fruit and dark honey notes. In between lies everything from peachy to roasted chestnut to burnt caramel.\n\nThis is why oolong is the most complex and variable of the six types — and why many experienced tea drinkers consider it the most rewarding category to explore.\n\nFlavour profile: Varies enormously by oxidation and roast level. Light oolongs: pale gold, floral, creamy, orchid. Dark oolongs: deep amber, toasty, caramelised, dried fruit, dark roast. High-mountain oolongs: clean, mineral, extraordinarily fragrant.\n\nTypical origins: Almost exclusively China and Taiwan. China: Fujian province (Tie Guan Yin from Anxi, rock oolongs from Wuyi — Da Hong Pao, Shui Xian, Rou Gui). Taiwan: Ali Shan, Li Shan, Da Yu Ling (high-mountain ball-rolled oolongs), Dong Ding.\n\nKey examples: Tie Guan Yin (Iron Goddess of Mercy) — from lightly roasted to heavily roasted styles. Da Hong Pao (Big Red Robe) — Wuyi rock oolong, dark and intensely mineral. Ali Shan — Taiwan high-mountain, creamy and floral.\n\n────────────────────────────────────────\nTYPE 5: BLACK TEA\n────────────────────────────────────────\nOxidation level: 85–100% (full or near-full)\nKey processing: Wither → rolling (which breaks cell walls thoroughly) → full oxidation until the leaf turns copper-to-brown → fixation (final firing that halts oxidation and removes moisture).\n\nWhat this produces: Maximum theaflavin and thearubigin production — giving black tea its characteristic deep amber to near-black liquor, brisk mouthfeel, and malty, robust flavour. The fresh green compounds are almost entirely converted. Black tea has the boldest flavour and the highest tolerance for additions like milk and sugar.\n\nFlavour profile: Deep amber to red-brown liquor. Bold and brisk. Malty (particularly Assam and Kenyan). Some black teas from high-altitude regions retain remarkable complexity: Darjeeling first flush has a light, muscatel quality despite being technically black tea; Yunnan Dian Hong has a distinctive chocolate-cocoa note from its high proportion of golden bud tips.\n\nTypical origins: Assam and Darjeeling (India), Kenya, Sri Lanka (Ceylon), Yunnan (China), Fujian (China — Keemun/Qimen).\n\nKey examples: Assam — malty and bold. Darjeeling first flush — light-bodied black with muscatel floral notes. Keemun — Fujian province, wine-like and fruity. Yunnan Dian Hong — golden-tipped, cocoa and honey.\n\nPROCESSING VARIANT — CTC (Cut-Tear-Curl): Many commercial black teas are not orthodox whole-leaf but CTC — mechanically cut into uniform small pellets that infuse very quickly and very strongly. Most teabags contain CTC Assam or Kenyan tea. CTC sacrifices nuance for consistency and speed.\n\n────────────────────────────────────────\nTYPE 6: PU-ERH TEA\n────────────────────────────────────────\nOxidation level: N/A — pu-erh undergoes a fundamentally different transformation (microbial fermentation, not enzymatic oxidation)\nKey processing: The leaf is first processed into mao cha — a sun-dried, minimal-fixation green tea base — then either:\n• Sheng (raw/unaged): Pressed into cakes and aged naturally for months to decades. Microbial communities (fungi and bacteria) slowly transform the leaf chemistry. Young sheng is green and assertive, often bitter and astringent. Aged sheng (10+ years) becomes smooth, earthy, and complex.\n• Shou (ripe): The mao cha undergoes a controlled wet-piling fermentation process (wo dui) for 45–60 days, during which moistened leaf piles are turned regularly and inoculated with microbial cultures. This accelerates the transformation that natural ageing would take decades to achieve.\n\nWhat this produces: A tea unlike any other — earthy, smooth, and complex. Notes of forest floor, mushroom, dark chocolate, leather, and dried fruit in aged versions. Shou pu-erh is immediately approachable; sheng pu-erh rewards patience.\n\nFlavour profile: Deep amber to near-black liquor (shou), golden-orange (young sheng), or darkening with age (aged sheng). Earthy, smooth, complex. Forest floor, dried fruit, dark chocolate, umami. Minimal astringency in good-quality aged examples. Can produce hui gan (returning sweetness) — a wave of sweetness at the back of the throat after swallowing.\n\nTypical origins: Almost exclusively Yunnan province, China. The Camellia sinensis used for pu-erh is typically the large-leaf Yunnan variety (sometimes called var. assamica sinensis or a closely related sub-variety), and production is regulated by geographic indication — genuine pu-erh must come from Yunnan.\n\nKey examples: Sheng pu-erh from Menghai (earthy and medicinal), Yiwu (fruity and refined), Bingdao (expensive, elegant). Shou pu-erh from Menghai Tea Factory (standard-bearer, widely available).\n\nCONNECTION BACK TO SECTION 1: Pu-erh and the other five types remind us of a fact from our very first section — all of this remarkable variety comes from one species, Camellia sinensis, which a mythological emperor discovered in Yunnan, the very region that produces pu-erh. The wheel comes full circle."
