          "blockId": "sec-types-block-09",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "A QUICK REFERENCE TABLE\n\nTea Type | Oxidation | Fixation Method | Flavour Character | Key Origins\n---------|-----------|-----------------|-------------------|------------\nWhite    | 0–15%     | None (wither/dry) | Delicate, honeyed, floral | Fujian (China)\nGreen    | 0%        | Pan-fire or steam | Vegetal, grassy, umami | China, Japan\nYellow   | 0–10%     | Pan-fire + men huan | Mellow, smooth, gentle | Hunan, Sichuan (China)\nOolong   | 15–85%    | Pan-fire (after partial oxidation) | Floral to roasted, hugely variable | Fujian (China), Taiwan\nBlack    | 85–100%   | Final firing (after full oxidation) | Malty, bold, brisk | India, Kenya, Sri Lanka\nPu-erh   | Fermented | Sun-dry + wet-pile or ageing | Earthy, smooth, complex | Yunnan (China)\n\nKEY TERMS FOR THIS SECTION\n\n• Polyphenol oxidase (PPO) — the enzyme in tea leaves that drives oxidation when cell walls are broken and the leaf is exposed to oxygen\n• Oxidation — the enzymatic conversion of catechins into theaflavins and thearubigins; the master variable distinguishing most tea types\n• Fixation (sha qing) — the heat step that denatures PPO and halts oxidation; timing determines the tea type\n• Pan-firing — Chinese fixation method using a hot wok or drum; produces toasty, chestnut notes\n• Steaming — Japanese fixation method using brief steam; preserves vegetal, umami, seaweed character\n• Withering — post-harvest moisture loss that softens the leaf for processing\n• Rolling — cell wall damage and shaping step; enables oxidation in black and oolong teas\n• Men huan — the smothering step unique to yellow tea; produces mellow smoothness\n• Mao cha — the raw, sun-dried green tea base from which pu-erh is made\n• Sheng (raw) pu-erh — naturally aged pu-erh; transforms slowly over years with microbial activity\n• Shou (ripe) pu-erh — accelerated wet-pile fermented pu-erh; mimics aged sheng in weeks\n• Theaflavins — bright, golden-orange compounds formed by oxidation; contribute brightness and briskness\n• Thearubigins — deep amber-brown compounds formed by prolonged oxidation; contribute body and depth\n• CTC (Cut-Tear-Curl) — mechanical processing producing small, uniform pellets for fast-infusing commercial tea\n• Hui gan — the 'returning sweetness' sensation generated after swallowing quality pu-erh or aged tea\n• Wo dui — the wet-piling fermentation process used to make shou pu-erh"
