      "contentBlocks": [
        {
          "blockId": "sec-preparation-block-01",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "By now you know what tea is (Section 1), what plant it comes from and where that plant grows (Section 2), and how processing creates six distinct types from one leaf (Section 3). That knowledge lives in the garden and the factory. This section is about what happens in your hands — in the sixty seconds between picking up a kettle and lifting a cup to your mouth.\n\nThe good news: there are only four variables that really matter. Control these four things correctly and you will get a good cup from almost any decent tea. Get them wrong and you can ruin a £100 tea just as effectively as a £2 one.\n\nThe four variables are:\n1. Water temperature\n2. Steeping time\n3. Leaf-to-water ratio\n4. Vessel\n\nThere is a fifth — water quality — that matters enough to discuss, but less frequently than the four above.\n\nHere is the key insight before we go into each one: these variables are not arbitrary rules handed down by tea tradition. They are consequences of chemistry. Once you understand WHY a given temperature is correct for a given tea — which compounds you are trying to extract, and which you are trying to avoid — you will never need to memorise a table again. You will be able to derive the parameters for any tea you encounter from first principles.\n\nTHE COOKING ANALOGY\n\nThink of brewing tea the way a cook thinks about a recipe. A good cook doesn't memorise a single fixed setting for every dish; they understand what heat does to protein, what acid does to colour, what salt does to water's boiling point. With that understanding, they can adapt any recipe and fix problems on the fly.\n\nA baker encountering a new dough recipe with no stated oven temperature looks at the ingredients and reasons backward: this is an enriched dough with butter and eggs (fat slows browning, sugar caramelises), and it has high hydration (needs a moderate oven to allow steam to escape before crust sets). They derive the temperature from the dough's composition, not from a lookup table.\n\nThat is exactly the skill you are building here. The 'dough composition' for tea is its type and processing; the 'oven parameters' are temperature, time, and ratio. Know the type, derive the parameters."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-preparation-block-02",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "VARIABLE 1: WATER TEMPERATURE\n\nThis is the most consequential single variable, and the one most commonly mishandled.\n\nThe rule most people follow — boiling water for all tea — is wrong for most tea types. Here is why.\n\nTea leaves contain several classes of compounds, and they dissolve into water at different rates depending on temperature:\n\n• L-theanine and amino acids (umami, sweetness): dissolve readily even in cool water, from about 40°C upward\n• Flavour aromatics (floral, grassy, fruity notes): volatile and heat-sensitive; high temperatures cause them to evaporate off quickly rather than staying in solution\n• Catechins and polyphenols (bitterness, astringency): require higher temperatures to dissolve at significant rates; at low temperatures they extract slowly and in modest quantities\n• Caffeine: requires higher temperatures for efficient extraction\n\nThis means:\n\nAt 100°C, you extract everything — including massive amounts of catechins and caffeine, which overwhelm the delicate aromatic and umami compounds. For a delicate green tea or white tea, boiling water produces a flat, bitter, harsh cup in which everything nuanced has been cooked off and everything harsh has been extracted at full force.\n\nAt 70°C, you extract L-theanine and aromatics efficiently while leaving catechin extraction at a much lower rate. The result — for a tea like Gyokuro or a fine Taiwanese oolong — is a cup of extraordinary sweetness, floral complexity, and umami richness, with minimal bitterness.\n\nFor black teas and pu-erh — which have already had their catechins converted to theaflavins and thearubigins by oxidation — high temperatures are appropriate. The theaflavins extract well at high temperatures and contribute the briskness and brightness you want. There is no delicate catechin-aromatic balance to protect.\n\nTHE DERIVATION PRINCIPLE: the correct temperature for any tea follows from its oxidation level.\n• Zero or low oxidation (white, green, yellow, light oolong): use cooler water to protect aromatics and limit catechin extraction\n• Moderate oxidation (medium oolong): moderate temperature\n• High oxidation or fermentation (black, dark oolong, pu-erh): use near-boiling water; catechins have been converted, and theaflavins need the heat\n\nThis is not a memorisation rule. It is a reasoning chain. You now own it regardless of what tea you encounter."
        },
