          "blockId": "sec-preparation-block-05",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "VARIABLE 2: STEEPING TIME AND THE EXTRACTION CURVE\n\nSteeping time and temperature work together — they are two axes of the same extraction process. Understanding both means understanding the extraction curve.\n\nWhen you add a tea leaf to hot water, compounds begin dissolving immediately. But they dissolve at different rates. In the first 30–60 seconds of steeping, amino acids (including L-theanine), light aromatic compounds, and some catechins enter the water. The liquor begins to develop flavour. This early extraction window is where the best of a tea lives.\n\nAs steeping continues, tannins — the compound class responsible for astringency — continue to extract at a steady rate long after the peak flavour compounds have reached their optimal concentration. If you continue steeping past the optimal window, tannins build and build, eventually overwhelming the pleasant flavour compounds you were trying to extract. The result is harsh, mouth-coating astringency and bitterness.\n\nThe COMMON MISCONCEPTION is that longer steeping equals stronger tea. It does not. Longer steeping equals more tannin extraction, which equals more astringency — not more flavour. If you want a stronger cup without bitterness, the correct lever is not time. It is leaf quantity.\n\nWANT STRONGER TEA? Add more leaf. Keep the time the same.\nWANT LIGHTER TEA? Use less leaf. Keep the time the same.\nWANT LESS BITTERNESS? Reduce time. Or reduce temperature. Or both.\n\nPRACTICAL STEEP TIMES\n\nFor Western-style brewing (single steep, mug or standard teapot):\n• White tea: 2–3 minutes\n• Green tea: 1–3 minutes (err shorter for delicate types)\n• Yellow tea: 2–3 minutes\n• Light oolong: 2–4 minutes\n• Black tea: 3–5 minutes\n• Pu-erh: 2–4 minutes\n\nFor Gongfu-style brewing (multiple short infusions, small vessel): 10–45 seconds per infusion, with parameters varying by tea type and infusion number (more in the Gongfu section below).\n\nVARIABLE 3: LEAF-TO-WATER RATIO\n\nThe standard Western ratio is approximately 2–3 grams of loose leaf per 200ml of water (roughly one teaspoon for most teas, though leaf density varies widely — a teaspoon of fluffy white peony weighs much less than a teaspoon of tightly rolled ball oolong).\n\nGongfu style uses significantly higher ratios — typically 5–8 grams per 100ml — which is why each infusion is so brief. The high concentration means flavour compounds extract within seconds, and the multiple-infusion approach allows the tea to evolve over 4–10+ steepings.\n\nA note on ball-rolled teas: oolongs like Taiwanese Ali Shan are rolled into tight pellets that look small but open dramatically in hot water. If you are measuring by volume (teaspoons) rather than weight (grams), use more than you think you need — the dry pellets occupy much less space than the fully unfurled leaf."
