          "blockId": "sec-preparation-block-07",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "VARIABLE 4: VESSEL MATERIAL\n\nThe vessel you brew in is not just aesthetic. It affects the tea in at least three measurable ways: heat retention, chemical interaction, and sometimes flavour contribution.\n\nGLASS\nPros: Completely chemically neutral — glass adds nothing to the tea and takes nothing away. Visually beautiful — you can watch the colour deepen and the leaves unfurl. Ideal for teas where appearance is part of the experience (high-grade Chinese greens and whites).\nCons: Poor heat retention — glass loses heat quickly, which matters for long-steep Western-style teas. Not ideal for Gyokuro or teas brewed at low temperature, which need to stay in that temperature window.\n\nPORCELAIN AND CERAMIC\nThe neutral standard. Good heat retention, completely neutral flavour interaction, and suitable for all tea types. The thin-walled bone china teacup beloved of British tea culture is a refined version of this — thin walls mean the tea reaches lip temperature quickly, maximising aroma perception as you drink.\n\nYIXING (ZISHA) CLAY\nThis is the most storied vessel in tea culture. Yixing clay, from Jiangsu province in China, is micro-porous — meaning it has a very fine, unglazed surface with tiny pores that absorb trace compounds from the tea with each use. Over years of use with the same tea type, a Yixing teapot develops a 'seasoning' — a build-up of tea compounds that subtly enhances subsequent brews of that tea. The traditional practice is to dedicate one Yixing pot to one tea type and never wash it with soap.\n\nYixing pots also have excellent heat retention and a pleasing weight and tactile quality. Whether the seasoning effect is chemically significant enough to taste is debated — some specialists believe the effect is real but modest; others point to psychological enhancement. What is not debated is that Yixing pots have been the vessel of choice for serious Chinese tea brewing for over four centuries, and that their heat retention and surface area characteristics are objectively distinct from glass or porcelain.\n\nIMPORTANT CONNECTION: In Section 6 (Ceremony), you will encounter the Yixing pot again in the context of Chinese Gongfu Cha ceremony — where vessel choice is not just functional but philosophical. The same object you are using as a brewing tool here is, in that context, an expression of aesthetic values and cultural identity. That continuity — the same variables serving different purposes in different contexts — is one of the most interesting threads in all of tea.\n\nCAST IRON (TETSUBIN)\nJapanese cast iron teapots provide exceptional heat retention — the best of any common vessel material. Ideal for teas brewed at high temperatures (black, pu-erh) where you want the temperature maintained across a slow Western-style steep. The interior of a tetsubin is typically enamelled to prevent rust. An unenamelled tetsubin (traditional style) is a water-heating vessel only — it should not hold tea directly, as the iron reacts with tannic acid.\n\nGAIWAN\nThe lidded bowl used in Chinese Gongfu brewing. The lid can be angled to strain the leaves when pouring. It offers precise control of pour temperature and speed, and its wide surface area encourages rapid cooling — useful for teas needing lower temperatures. Porcelain gaiwans are neutral; Yixing gaiwans behave like Yixing teapots.\n\nVARIABLE 5: WATER QUALITY\n\nWater is 99%+ of your cup of tea. Its quality is not irrelevant.\n\nThe ideal brewing water is soft and slightly mineral — roughly 50–150 ppm total dissolved solids (TDS). Heavily chlorinated tap water can suppress delicate aromatics and leave an off-taste. Very hard water (high calcium and magnesium) interacts with tea polyphenols and can produce a dull, flat flavour and a scummy surface film on the cup.\n\nIf you are brewing fine teas and notice disappointing results, water quality is worth investigating. Filtered tap water (a simple Brita-style filter) removes chlorine and reduces hardness enough to make a meaningful difference. For the finest teas — a premium Gyokuro or aged pu-erh — specialist low-mineral spring waters (around 30–50 ppm TDS) are used by serious practitioners. For everyday tea, filtered or good tap water is sufficient."
