      "contentBlocks": [
        {
          "blockId": "sec-preparation-block-09",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Everything we have covered so far assumes a single-steep brewing approach: put leaf in vessel, add hot water, wait, pour, drink. This is Western-style brewing, and it is perfectly good for most everyday tea.\n\nBut there is another approach that reveals something Western-style brewing hides: how a tea evolves.\n\nGONGFU-STYLE BREWING\n\nGongfu Cha (工夫茶, literally 'tea with effort') is the Chinese approach to brewing fine teas using a small vessel, a high leaf-to-water ratio, and multiple very short infusions. Rather than making one cup from one steep, you make six, eight, ten, or more infusions from the same leaves, each one tasted and compared.\n\nThe key equipment:\n• Small vessel: a Yixing teapot or porcelain gaiwan, typically 60–150ml capacity\n• Cha hai (fairness pitcher): an intermediate pouring vessel; the full infusion is poured from the brewing vessel into the cha hai before being distributed to individual cups, ensuring uniform strength for everyone\n• Small tasting cups: 30–50ml, designed for slow, attentive sipping\n• The brewing surface: a tea tray or tea table that catches overflow and rinse water\n\nTHE GONGFU RATIO AND TIMING\n\nWhere Western brewing uses roughly 2–3g per 200ml and steeps for 3–5 minutes, Gongfu uses 5–8g per 100ml and steeps for 5–30 seconds (sometimes less). The extremely high leaf-to-water ratio means that even a very brief infusion extracts significant flavour. \n\nCrucially, each successive infusion of the same leaves is slightly different. The first infusion (often preceded by a quick rinse pour that is discarded) opens the leaf. The second and third infusions are typically the peak — the leaves are fully hydrated, the flavour compounds are extracting at optimal rate, and the liquor is at its most complex and balanced. By the fifth or sixth infusion, the lighter compounds have diminished and the tea begins to taste sweeter, earthier, softer. By the eighth or ninth, it has transformed again.\n\nTasting the evolution of a tea across infusions is an entirely different experience from drinking one cup of the same tea. It rewards patience and attention. It is why Chinese tea culture developed an entire philosophy and ceremony (Gongfu Cha) around this approach — something we will explore fully in Section 6.\n\nWHY WESTERN STYLE IS ALSO FINE\n\nThis is not a case where one approach is better. Western-style brewing is faster, requires less equipment, and produces a reliable, pleasant cup. For an everyday builder's tea or a casual mug of Sencha, the Western approach is entirely appropriate.\n\nGongfu is better suited to: fine teas where the leaf-cost justifies multiple infusions; oolongs and pu-erhs that genuinely evolve and improve across infusions; and situations where the act of brewing is itself part of what you want from the experience.\n\nThe two styles serve different intentions. Understanding both means you can match your approach to your context."
