          "content": "TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE: DIAGNOSING YOUR CUP\n\nUsing the variables framework, most brewing problems can be diagnosed quickly:\n\nToo bitter → Over-extraction of catechins/tannins\n  Causes: water too hot; time too long; ratio too high\n  Fixes: lower temperature; reduce steep time; use less leaf\n\nToo astringent (dry, gripping mouthfeel) → Tannin over-extraction specifically\n  Causes: time too long is the primary culprit; temperature too high compounds it\n  Fixes: reduce steep time first; check temperature second\n\nToo weak / flat / watery → Under-extraction\n  Causes: water not hot enough; time too short; too little leaf\n  Fixes: check temperature; increase time slightly; add more leaf\n\nNo aroma → Volatile aromatics lost\n  Causes: water too hot (aromatics boiled off); tea stored poorly (stale); old tea\n  Fixes: reduce temperature; check storage conditions (airtight, cool, dark, away from other aromas)\n\nOff-taste (soapy, chlorine, metallic) → Water quality\n  Causes: chlorinated tap water; reactive vessel material; old water in kettle re-boiled\n  Fixes: use filtered water; descale kettle; do not re-boil water; avoid reactive vessels\n\nKEY TERMS FOR THIS SECTION\n\n• Extraction — the process by which compounds in tea dissolve into water; rate controlled by temperature, time, leaf-to-water ratio, and leaf particle size\n• Over-extraction — too many tannins extracted, producing harsh bitterness and mouth-coating astringency\n• Under-extraction — insufficient flavour compounds dissolved, producing a weak, flat, or watery cup\n• Variable-temperature kettle — a kettle with precise temperature settings, allowing temperatures below boiling\n• Western-style brewing — single steep using a larger vessel, lower leaf ratio, and 3–5 minute steep time\n• Gongfu Cha (工夫茶) — Chinese multi-infusion brewing using a small vessel, high leaf ratio, and multiple short steeps of 5–30 seconds\n• Cha hai (fairness pitcher) — intermediate pouring vessel used in Gongfu to equalise infusion strength before distributing to cups\n• Gaiwan — lidded Chinese brewing bowl offering precise temperature and pour control\n• Yixing / Zisha — micro-porous Jiangsu clay used for traditional Chinese teapots; develops seasoning with dedicated use\n• Tetsubin — Japanese cast iron kettle or teapot with exceptional heat retention\n• TDS (Total Dissolved Solids) — a measure of mineral content in water; optimal for tea brewing at approximately 50–150 ppm\n• Leaf-to-water ratio — the proportion of tea leaf to water volume; higher ratios require shorter steep times"
