      "contentBlocks": [
        {
          "blockId": "sec-global-cultures-block-01",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Before we travel the world cup by cup, an analogy to orient you.\n\nThink about music. 'Blues' is a specific musical tradition with roots in the American South — particular chord structures, a specific emotional vocabulary, a history bound up with African American experience and suffering. But if you ask whether blues music is 'authentic' in London, Lagos, Tokyo, or São Paulo, the question becomes complicated. Those cities have their own blues traditions, locally rooted but globally informed, that have evolved into something distinct. Is a Tokyo blues bar playing authentic blues? Is a Nigerian musician who grew up listening to Muddy Waters and developed their own style less authentic than someone from Mississippi?\n\nTea works exactly the same way.\n\nThere is a point of origin — China — and a set of practices that developed there over more than a thousand years. But tea then spread, through trade and colonialism and cultural exchange, into dozens of cultures that made it completely their own. Indian masala chai is not 'inauthentic tea' — it is the tea tradition that India developed from the raw material that British colonialism introduced to them. Moroccan atai is not 'a deviation from proper tea' — it is the fully realised tea culture of North Africa, with its own logic, history, and meaning.\n\nThe question 'which of these is authentic?' misunderstands how culture works. Every tradition in this section is authentic. Each one evolved in response to local ingredients, social needs, climate, history, and taste. Understanding them side by side does not reveal a hierarchy — it reveals a diversity that makes the story of tea one of the most interesting stories in all of food culture.\n\nWith that framing in place: let's go."
        }
      ],

