          "content": "BRITAIN: CLASS IN A CUP\n\nYou already know from Section 1 that the Commutation Act of 1784 made tea affordable for ordinary British people for the first time. What happened next is one of the most complete cultural transformations in modern food history.\n\nWithin two generations, tea went from a luxury of the wealthy to the defining national beverage of all classes — but it did not become identical across classes. It splintered into two distinct traditions, and the language used to describe them encodes the class structure of Victorian Britain so precisely that even today, confusing the terms is a social signal.\n\nAFTERNOON TEA\n\nAfternoon Tea was created, according to popular tradition, by Anna Maria Stanhope, the 7th Duchess of Bedford, around 1840. She found herself hungry in the long interval between the fashionable light lunch and the late dinner (sometimes as late as 8 or 9 pm) and began having a tray of tea, bread and butter, and small cakes brought to her room in the afternoon. She began inviting friends to join her. The practice spread rapidly through aristocratic and upper-middle-class society.\n\nAfternoon Tea is characterised by:\n• A light, elegant spread: finger sandwiches (cucumber, smoked salmon, egg mayonnaise), scones with clotted cream and jam, pastries and cakes\n• Fine bone china cups and saucers\n• A choice of teas, typically Darjeeling, Assam, Earl Grey, or similar\n• A low, parlour or drawing-room setting — a low table, not a dining table\n• A social occasion: conversation, presentation, refinement\n• Timing: approximately 3–5 pm\n\nAFTERNOON TEA IS NOT A MEAL. It is a social performance, a graceful bridge between the fashionable afternoon and the late evening.\n\nHIGH TEA\n\nHigh Tea is an entirely different thing — and the confusion between the two is one of the most persistent and consequential errors in popular understanding of British food culture.\n\nHigh Tea was the working-class evening meal, taken at a high dining table (hence 'high' — it refers to the furniture, not social elevation) typically between 5 and 7 pm. It was a substantial, hearty meal: cold meats, pies, bread and butter, cooked dishes, baked beans, cheese — real food after a long working day. Tea was the drink that accompanied this meal, strong and plentiful.\n\nThe distinction matters because the two traditions reflect fundamentally different relationships to tea:\n• Afternoon Tea: tea as luxury, theatre, social display\n• High Tea: tea as sustenance, comfort, democratic pleasure\n\nThe builder who drinks a strong, milky, heavily sweetened 'builder's tea' from a large mug is participating in the High Tea tradition. The guest at Claridge's paying £70 for Afternoon Tea is participating in the Afternoon Tea tradition. These are not the same tradition with different price tags. They are different traditions that reflect different historical relationships to tea.\n\nTODAY'S BRITISH TEA CULTURE\n\nContemporary British tea culture is predominantly descended from the High Tea tradition — strong, black (or with milk), often from a teabag, frequently offered as a gesture of comfort or hospitality. The phrase 'put the kettle on' is one of the most common social responses to any situation — joy, grief, crisis, reunion. The average British person drinks approximately 2–3 cups of tea per day. The nation consumes around 100 million cups per day in total.\n\nThe tea itself is almost always a blend of Assam and Kenyan CTC black tea — robust, designed to withstand milk, simple and reliable. This is not because British tea drinkers lack sophistication; it is because this specific combination was optimised, over two centuries of commercial development, for exactly this purpose."
