          "blockId": "sec-global-cultures-block-06",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "CHINA: THE ORIGINAL AND THE EVERYDAY\n\nChina is where tea began, and it is where tea culture is simultaneously the oldest and the most layered. Chinese daily tea-drinking is not a single thing — it varies by region, social setting, age group, and occasion in ways that would take a lifetime to fully map.\n\nFor everyday purposes, Chinese tea culture can be understood through two lenses:\n\nDAILY TEA: Most urban Chinese adults drink tea throughout the day — green tea or oolong in a personal glass or lidded cup (a gaiwan or a zhong), often refilled multiple times. The tea is personal, functional, and ambient. It is not a social performance; it is simply what you drink, in the way that water is what you drink.\n\nYUM CHA: The Cantonese tradition of yum cha — literally 'drink tea' — is one of the most distinctive tea-social traditions in the world. Yum cha involves visiting a dim sum restaurant, typically in the morning or at lunchtime, and ordering small plates of dumplings, steamed buns, and other dim sum dishes while drinking tea continuously throughout the meal. The tea is secondary to the dim sum but essential to the rhythm of the meal — it cleanses the palate between dishes and facilitates the long, leisurely, multi-generational gathering that is the real point.\n\nThe teas served at yum cha are typically robust and digestive: pu-erh, chrysanthemum, or jasmine-scented green tea. Pu-erh in particular is prized because its earthy, smooth character and digestive properties make it an ideal companion to the rich, fatty dim sum dishes.\n\nThe practice of tapping two fingers on the table when someone pours your tea is a small but deeply ingrained gesture of thanks, originating in a story about a Qing Dynasty emperor who used to disguise himself as a commoner and pour tea for his companions — who could not bow to acknowledge an emperor without breaking the disguise, so they tapped their bent fingers to simulate a bow instead."
