          "blockId": "sec-global-cultures-block-07",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "JAPAN: DAILY TEA AND THE CULTURE OF FRESHNESS\n\nJapan's everyday tea culture is almost entirely green. The national default tea is sencha — a steamed, needle-shaped green tea that represents approximately 70% of Japanese tea production and is drunk at almost every meal, in offices, and at home. The Japanese relationship with sencha is characterised by freshness: shincha, the first flush of the year (April–May), is treated with reverence similar to a new wine vintage, consumed quickly and appreciatively.\n\nBeyond sencha, the Japanese daily tea landscape includes:\n• Hojicha: roasted green tea with a nutty, caramel warmth and very low caffeine. Often served to children and the elderly, or drunk in the evenings when caffeine is unwanted.\n• Genmaicha: green tea mixed with roasted brown rice, giving it a toasty, popcorn-like character. A comfort tea, widely accessible and unintimidating.\n• Bancha: a lower-grade green tea from later harvests. More everyday and less nuanced than sencha but entirely functional.\n\nJAPAN AND RTD TEA: Japan was the pioneer of ready-to-drink bottled tea — unsweetened or very lightly sweetened green tea in plastic bottles or cans, sold from the ubiquitous vending machines that cover the country. Japanese RTD tea is generally high quality and culturally continuous with the tradition — a genuine cup of good sencha in a bottle, not an artificially flavoured approximation. This innovation, developed in the 1980s, was one of the most significant contributions Japan made to global tea culture."
