          "blockId": "sec-global-cultures-block-09",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "MOROCCO: THE THREE GLASSES OF LIFE\n\nMorocco is one of the world's highest per-capita tea consuming nations, and its tea culture — built around atai, mint tea — is one of the most ritualised and socially laden in the world.\n\nAtai is made from Chinese gunpowder green tea (small, tightly rolled pellets of green tea that unfurl in hot water), brewed strong and then combined with generous bundles of fresh spearmint and very large quantities of cane sugar. The preparation and serving of atai is a social act, traditionally performed by the man of the household or a respected elder.\n\nTHE THREE-GLASS RITUAL: Moroccan custom dictates that guests are offered three glasses of tea, each poured sequentially with the same batch of tea-and-mint. The flavour evolves across the three glasses — the first strong and bitter, the second balanced and rich, the third sweet and mild. A Moroccan proverb associates the three glasses with life itself: the first glass is as bitter as life, the second as sweet as love, the third as gentle as death.\n\nTHE HIGH-POUR TECHNIQUE: Atai is poured from a significant height — sometimes half a metre or more — into the small glass. This serves two functions: it aerates the tea (dissolving more oxygen and creating a light froth on the surface), and it is a display of skill and hospitality. A host who pours beautifully is demonstrating care and mastery. A froth-less pour suggests haste or inattention.\n\nCONNECTION TO BREWING VARIABLES (Section 4): The high-pour technique is an intuitive solution to a brewing problem. By pouring from height and allowing air to mix in, the host is essentially oxygenating the tea — a technique that smooths astringency and brightens flavour. This is the same principle behind swirling wine or aerating a sauce. The cultural practice and the chemistry align perfectly, even though no one in the tradition describes it in those terms.\n\nRefusing a glass of Moroccan mint tea is considered impolite — the serving of tea is an act of hospitality and trust, and declining it communicates the opposite of what a guest typically wants to convey."
