          "blockId": "sec-global-cultures-block-11",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "TURKEY: A NATION THAT DRINKS BY THE GLASS\n\nTurkey is one of the world's largest per-capita tea consumers — ahead of both China and Britain. The Turkish national tea is çay (pronounced 'chai'), a strong, plain black tea grown domestically along the Black Sea coast (Turkey established its own tea industry in the 1930s, one of the few examples of a non-colonial tea-growing nation).\n\nTurkish çay is brewed in a çaydanlık — a distinctive double-stacked teapot where the lower pot holds boiling water and the upper pot holds a very strong tea concentrate. When serving, the concentrate is poured first, then diluted with hot water from the lower pot to the drinker's preference. This allows each person to drink their tea at exactly the strength they prefer, from very light to near-syrup.\n\nÇay is served in small tulip-shaped glasses without handles — their shape is said to be designed to show the deep amber colour of the tea beautifully and to allow the drinker to hold the glass without burning their fingers by gripping the rim. It is accompanied by a small amount of sugar (placed on the saucer, never stirred in — the Turkish drinker takes a sip of tea through the sugar cube clenched between the front teeth).\n\nTurkish tea culture is deeply public and democratic. Çay is served at virtually every social interaction — business meetings, street vendors, barber shops, carpet shops (where declining tea is the first signal that you are a serious customer rather than a browser). It is estimated that Turks drink an average of 3–4 cups of çay per day.\n\nKENYA: THE COLONIAL CHAIN IN A CUP\n\nKenya's tea story is a direct continuation of the colonial chain you traced in Section 1. British colonial agriculture established tea estates in the Kenyan highlands in the early 20th century, primarily to produce CTC black tea for the export market. Kenya is now the world's largest exporter of black tea by volume — a fact that would have been impossible to predict as recently as 1910.\n\nBut Kenya's domestic tea culture is not the same as its export product. The tea Kenyans drink at home is heavily adapted: very sweet, very milky, often brewed with the milk simmered in directly (rather than added after) — a preparation close to masala chai without the spices. This style traces directly back to Indian railway and plantation workers brought to Kenya by British colonial infrastructure projects, who transplanted their own chai culture to East Africa.\n\nThe specific chain: British colonial railways in India → Indian workers recruited for East African railway construction → chai culture transplanted to Kenya → local adoption and adaptation → today's Kenyan dawa (spiced tea variant) and plain sweet milk tea.\n\nThis is what cultural history looks like in a cup: a Chinese plant, grown on a British colonial plantation, brewed in a style derived from Indian workers, drunk by Kenyan people who have made it entirely their own.\n\nTIBET: THE WORLD'S MOST SURPRISING TEA\n\nFor sheer departure from expectation, nothing beats Tibetan butter tea — po cha.\n\nPo cha is made from strong black brick tea (traditionally a compressed, fermented tea similar to pu-erh), churned together with yak butter, salt, and sometimes soda in a cylindrical churn called a dongmo until it becomes a thick, emulsified, savoury drink.\n\nTo a palate accustomed to sweet or plain tea, po cha tastes almost nothing like tea at all — it is closer to a thin, salty broth with a faint tea note. This is not an accident. Tibet's high-altitude environment (averaging 4,500 metres) creates conditions of intense cold, caloric demand, and severe dehydration. Po cha is not a beverage chosen for pleasure; it is a functional food adapted to one of the most extreme human environments on Earth. The yak butter provides fat calories; the salt replaces electrolytes lost in altitude; the liquid provides hydration; the tea provides mild stimulant effect.\n\nA Tibetan household might consume 50–60 cups of po cha per day. Guests are expected to drink it as a form of hospitality; to refuse is a significant social slight. It is perhaps the clearest example in this entire course of tea being shaped by environment and necessity into something entirely unrecognisable from its origin form — and entirely appropriate for its context."
