          "blockId": "sec-global-cultures-block-12",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "TAIWAN AND THE WORLD: BUBBLE TEA AND THE LIVING EDGE\n\nThis section would be incomplete without addressing where tea culture is going — and for that, we look to Taiwan and the global phenomenon it created in the 1980s.\n\nBUBBLE TEA (BOBA)\n\nBubble tea — also called boba — was invented in Taiwan, most likely in Taichung in the 1980s, with competing claims from different tea shops about who added the first tapioca pearls to a sweetened iced tea. What is agreed: within a decade it had spread across Taiwan, then to Chinese diaspora communities worldwide, and by the 2000s–2010s it had become a global cultural phenomenon with dedicated shops in virtually every major city.\n\nBoba is tea — typically black or green, often with milk — served cold with chewy tapioca starch pearls at the bottom, drunk through an oversized straw. Thousands of variations exist: fruit teas, matcha lattes, taro milk teas, cheese-foam toppings. It is simultaneously a tea drink and a dessert, a beverage and a snack.\n\nCRITICAL NOTE: Bubble tea is NOT Japanese, despite being frequently and incorrectly associated with Japanese tea culture in Western media. Japan pioneered RTD bottled tea; Taiwan pioneered bubble tea. These are separate innovations from different countries that should not be confused.\n\nTHIRD-WAVE SPECIALTY TEA\n\nThe most current development in tea culture is the rise of what is sometimes called 'third-wave' or 'specialty' tea — borrowing the framing from the coffee industry's third-wave movement. Specialty tea shops apply single-origin sourcing, transparent producer relationships, seasonal specificity, and skilled preparation to tea in the way that specialty coffee applied these values to coffee from the 1990s onward.\n\nA third-wave tea shop might stock a Darjeeling first flush from a specific named garden, a specific harvest week, at a specific altitude — the equivalent of a single-origin, single-farm coffee. The shop will likely offer multiple brewing styles (Western, Gongfu), describe the tea's terroir and processing, and have staff who can guide a customer through a flight of teas the way a sommelier guides a wine tasting.\n\nThis movement is small but growing, and it represents the living edge of tea culture's evolution — proof that mis-cult-003's claim that 'tea culture is static and ancient' is demonstrably false."
