          "content": "THE TOOLS AND SEQUENCE OF CHADO\n\nChado uses a specific set of tools, each with its own name and place in the sequence:\n\n• Chawan (茶碗) — the tea bowl. The most important object in the ceremony. Hand-formed, often asymmetric. The host rotates the bowl before drinking so as not to drink from its 'front' — a gesture of humility and care for the object.\n• Chasen (茶筅) — the bamboo whisk. Made from a single piece of bamboo; different styles have different numbers of tines for thin tea (usucha) or thick tea (koicha). The chasen is one of the most technically demanding objects to make well.\n• Chashaku (茶杓) — a bamboo scoop used to measure powdered matcha from the natsume (tea caddy) into the bowl.\n• Fukusa (袱紗) — a folded silk cloth used to ritually clean the natsume and the ladle before the guest's eyes. The folding and unfolding of the fukusa is a practiced art, its precise folds a signature of the practitioner's school and seniority.\n• Natsume (棗) — the tea caddy containing the powdered matcha.\n• Kama (釜) — the iron kettle heating over a charcoal hearth (ro in winter, furo in summer). The sound of water heating in the kama — the 'wind in the pines' — is considered part of the ceremony's aesthetic.\n• Tokonoma (床の間) — the alcove in the tea room where a single hanging scroll (kakemono) and a single flower arrangement (chabana) are displayed. These are changed for each gathering to reflect the season, the occasion, and the host's intent for that specific meeting.\n• Nijiriguchi (躙口) — the small entry gate, approximately 60cm square, through which all guests must crawl or crouch to enter the tea room.\n\nTHE SEQUENCE\n\nA full formal ceremony (chaji) lasts several hours and includes a meal (kaiseki), a break in the garden, and then the tea service itself. For this overview, the tea preparation sequence runs as follows:\n\n1. The tea room is prepared: scroll hung, flower arranged, water heating in the kama, tools set in their places.\n2. Guests enter through the nijiriguchi and take their positions.\n3. The host enters and performs the ritual cleaning of the natsume and ladle with the fukusa.\n4. Matcha powder is measured from the natsume into the chawan with the chashaku.\n5. Hot water is ladled from the kama into the chawan.\n6. The matcha is whisked into a smooth froth with the chasen.\n7. The bowl is rotated and presented to the first guest. They receive it with a bow, rotate the bowl to avoid drinking from its 'face,' drink in three-and-a-half sips, wipe the rim, and return the bowl.\n8. The sequence continues until all guests are served.\n\nUsucha (thin tea) is the standard preparation. Koicha (thick tea) — a paste-like, highly concentrated bowl made with more matcha and less water — is reserved for formal occasions and is considered the more demanding and prestigious preparation.\n\nCONNECTION TO SECTION 1: Chado's matcha uses powdered tea — a direct descendant of the Song Dynasty powdered tea tradition that Buddhist monks brought to Japan in the 12th century. When Ming Dynasty China moved to loose-leaf tea, Japan kept the powdered form and developed it into Chado. The divergence between Chinese and Japanese tea culture is rooted in this specific historical moment."
