          "blockId": "sec-ceremony-block-07",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "CHINESE GONGFU CHA: THE CEREMONY OF EVOLUTION\n\nHistorical context: Gongfu Cha emerged in the Fujian and Guangdong regions of China during the Ming Dynasty — the same era that produced the loose-leaf brewing revolution you encountered in Section 1. Where Japan preserved and ritualised the Tang and Song Dynasty powdered tea traditions, China moved to loose-leaf and developed entirely new brewing practices. Gongfu Cha — literally 'tea made with skill and effort' — was the sophisticated expression of this new approach.\n\nPhilosophical core: Where Chado is about achieving a state through preparation, Gongfu Cha is about revealing a truth through time. The core insight of Gongfu Cha is that a fine tea has a life arc — it evolves across infusions, from the tightly wound first steep to the fully open, complex middle steeps to the gentle, fading conclusion. To drink a tea in a single Western-style infusion is to know only one chapter of its story. Gongfu Cha reads the whole book.\n\nTHE TOOLS (revisiting from Section 4 with ceremonial meaning added):\n\n• Gaiwan or Yixing teapot — the brewing vessel. In Gongfu Cha, the choice between gaiwan (neutral, precise, reveals the tea without influence) and Yixing (micro-porous, develops seasoning, becomes part of the tea over time) is itself a philosophical statement about the relationship between practitioner and material.\n\n• Cha hai (公道杯, fairness cup) — the intermediate pitcher. When the infusion is complete, the full brew is poured immediately into the cha hai, ending extraction and equalising the concentration. This ensures every guest receives the same tea — the same strength, the same character. The name means 'fairness' or 'justice,' and the object enacts the social value it names.\n\n• Wen xiang bei (聞香杯, sniffing cup) — a tall, narrow cup used in some Gongfu Cha traditions, particularly for oolongs, to capture the aroma of the liquor before pouring it into the drinking cup. The tea is poured from the sniffing cup into the wide drinking cup; the empty sniffing cup retains the aroma and is held to the nose. The olfactory dimension of the tea — its fragrance as it clings to warm ceramic — is treated as worthy of dedicated attention.\n\n• The tea tray — a wooden or bamboo surface, often with a drainage basin, that catches rinse water and overflow. The tea tray makes the practice of rinsing (warming vessels with water before use) and discarding water clean and unfussy.\n\nTHE SEQUENCE AND PHILOSOPHY:\n\nA formal Gongfu Cha session for oolongs or pu-erh might proceed: warm all vessels with boiling water, discard; insert leaf (high ratio, 5–8g per 100ml); brief rinse pour (5 seconds — discarded, this 'awakens' the leaf and flushes any surface dust); first infusion (20–30 seconds); pour into cha hai; distribute to cups; taste together. Subsequent infusions increase in duration by a few seconds each, tracking the tea's evolution.\n\nThe conversation during Gongfu Cha is typically about the tea itself — its colour, aroma, and character change with each infusion. This is not pedantry; it is the ceremony's subject matter. The tea's evolution IS what is being appreciated together.\n\nCONNECTION TO SECTION 4: You already know the brewing variables. In Gongfu Cha, those variables are not set-and-forget; they are in continuous dialogue with the tea's state. Each infusion is evaluated, and the next is adjusted: slightly longer, slightly hotter, slightly shorter, depending on what the tea is doing. The practitioner is not following a recipe but conducting a conversation.\n\nCONNECTION TO SECTION 5: In Section 5 you encountered Gongfu Cha as everyday Chinese practice — a way of brewing fine teas at home or in a teahouse. In this section we see that the same practice exists on a continuum: casual Gongfu Cha and ceremonial Gongfu Cha use the same tools and the same principles, differing only in the degree of ritual attention and social formality brought to the act."
