      "contentBlocks": [
        {
          "blockId": "sec-tasting-block-01",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Before we introduce the four-stage framework, we need to address a misconception that stops many people from engaging with structured tasting at all.\n\nThe misconception is this: tasting is purely subjective. 'I either like it or I don't' is the only meaningful response. Giving something a flavour description feels pretentious, arbitrary, or simply made up.\n\nThis view is understandable — and wrong. Here is why.\n\nTHE LANGUAGE LEARNING ANALOGY\n\nThink about what happens when you hear a language you do not know. The first time you hear, say, spoken Mandarin, it arrives as undifferentiated sound — a flow of syllables you cannot parse or distinguish. There are patterns in it, structure, meaning — but without the vocabulary and grammar to decode them, your brain processes it as noise.\n\nNow think about what happens after you have studied Mandarin for a year. The same audio signal — physically identical — is now full of information. You hear individual syllables, tone distinctions, familiar words, the structure of sentences. The signal has not changed at all. What changed is the listening apparatus you brought to it.\n\nSensory tasting works identically. Before you have vocabulary for tea flavour, a cup of Darjeeling first flush arrives as an undifferentiated pleasant experience. After you have the vocabulary — 'muscatel,' 'apricot stone,' 'floral,' 'light body,' 'dry finish' — the same cup reveals structure, character, and information you could not previously access. The tea has not changed. What changed is the tasting apparatus you brought to it.\n\nThis is not a claim that trained tasters experience more pleasure than untrained ones — preferences are personal and perfectly valid however they form. It is a claim that vocabulary opens perception. The trained taster and the untrained taster are drinking the same tea, but they are having different experiences of it. The trained taster is not showing off; they are seeing more.\n\nA SECOND IMPORTANT POINT: liking and describing are two separate skills. You can develop excellent tasting vocabulary for teas you do not enjoy. You can love a tea intensely without being able to describe it precisely. The two skills coexist independently. Developing one does not replace the other — it enriches both."
        }
