      "contentBlocks": [
        {
          "blockId": "sec-tasting-block-02",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Professional tea tasters — working for auction houses, importers, quality control labs, and speciality shops — use a standardised evaluation framework. Its power is not that it tells you what to think, but that it ensures you look at everything worth looking at, in a useful order, before reaching any conclusion.\n\nThe framework has four stages: Appearance, Aroma, Taste, Finish.\n\nNote the order: Aroma comes before Taste. This is not arbitrary. Approximately 70–80% of what we experience as 'taste' is actually olfactory — it arrives via the retronasal pathway, from the back of the mouth up through the nasopharynx to the olfactory receptors. The 'taste' of a strawberry is mostly smell, processed by the brain as a unified flavour experience. Tea is the same: what you perceive as 'flavour' when you drink tea is predominantly aroma molecules reaching olfactory receptors, not taste receptors on the tongue. Separating the stages and engaging the nose before the mouth is therefore not pedantry — it is perceptually accurate."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-tasting-block-03",
          "type": "image",
          "url": "PLACEHOLDER",
          "altText": "IMAGE PLACEHOLDER: A clean, professional-looking tasting framework diagram showing the four stages arranged horizontally or in a circular flow: (1) Appearance — with sub-labels: dry leaf, wet leaf, liquor colour/clarity; (2) Aroma — with sub-labels: dry leaf aroma, steam aroma, warmed cup aroma; (3) Taste — with sub-labels: first impression, mid-palate body, astringency, bitterness, specific notes; (4) Finish — with sub-labels: length (short/medium/long), hui gan, hou yun, character. Each stage should be visually distinct. Clean, instructional style suitable for a professional reference card."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-tasting-block-04",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "STAGE 1: APPEARANCE\n\nAppearance assessment happens twice: first with the dry leaf before brewing, and second with both the wet leaf and the liquor after brewing.\n\nDRY LEAF:\n• Colour: What colour are the leaves? Green (minimally oxidised), golden (tippy), brown-black (fully oxidised), grey-green (aged/fermented)? Colour already tells you something about the type and processing.\n• Shape: Flat and sword-like (Longjing)? Tightly rolled balls (Taiwanese oolong)? Twisted needles (Bi Luo Chun, Silver Needle)? The shape tells you about the rolling technique and therefore the processing style.\n• Uniformity: Are the leaves similar in size and colour, or wildly mixed? Uniformity suggests consistent quality sorting; unevenness suggests mixed-grade blending.\n• Visible tips: Are there golden or silver fuzzy bud tips visible? These are the least-processed parts of the young leaf — their presence in quantity suggests fine plucking.\n\nWET LEAF (after brewing):\n• How fully did the leaf open? Ball-rolled oolongs should be nearly fully unfurled; broken tea grades stay small.\n• What colour is the steeped leaf? Still partly green, or uniformly brown? This cross-checks the processing type.\n\nLIQUOR:\n• Colour: Pale gold (white/green), amber (oolong/black), deep red-brown (strong black/pu-erh)?\n• Clarity: Clear and bright? Or cloudy and dull? Cloudiness can suggest brewing temperature was too high (protein haze), the tea contains broken leaf particles, or the tea has 'chill haze' from cooling too quickly.\n• Depth: Translucent or opaque? Deep colour without opacity suggests theaflavin richness.\n\nCONNECTION TO SECTIONS 2 AND 3: Appearance directly reflects terroir and processing. The pale gold of a Gyokuro tells you it is minimally oxidised and shade-grown; the silver needle tips tell you it was plucked at the finest standard; the deep amber of an Assam tells you full oxidation has converted most catechins to theaflavins. You are reading the processing and botany in the cup before you taste a drop."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-tasting-block-05",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "STAGE 2: AROMA\n\nAroma evaluation has three moments, each yielding different information:\n\nDRY LEAF AROMA:\nBefore brewing, open the packet or caddy and inhale over the dry leaves. The dry aroma is often the purest expression of the tea's aromatic profile — firing and processing aromas are most concentrated here. A Tie Guan Yin oolong might reveal orchid and cream on the dry leaf; a Yunnan black might reveal cocoa and dried fruit; a Lapsang Souchong announces pine smoke immediately.\n\nSTEAM AROMA:\nImmediately after adding hot water, hold your nose over the cup (be careful — closer than comfortable distance is painful) and inhale the steam. The steam carries volatile aromatic compounds lifted by heat. This is often where the most vivid and fleeting impressions live. Floral notes are often strongest here.\n\nWARMED CUP AROMA:\nAfter pouring the tea from the cup (if using the Gongfu wen xiang bei technique) or after the cup has held hot tea and been emptied, inhale from the warmed vessel. As the cup cools, different aromatic layers reveal themselves — the low notes that were masked by the heat. This is a technique practiced seriously in Gongfu Cha and is worth trying even without the dedicated sniffing cup.\n\nAROMA VOCABULARY:\n\nHere is a working vocabulary organised by category:\n\nFLORAL: orchid, jasmine, rose, lily, honeysuckle, magnolia, violet\nVEGETAL: fresh grass, steamed spinach, seaweed (nori), cooked peas, artichoke, green bell pepper\nFRUITY: apricot, peach, muscatel (grape-skin/stone-fruit), dried fruit, citrus, tropical, berry\nTOASTY / NUTTY: roasted chestnut, toasted bread, biscuit, walnut, hazelnut, sesame, grain\nSMOKY / ROASTED: woodsmoke, charcoal, pine, campfire, dark roast coffee\nEARTHY / MINERAL: wet stone, forest floor, mushroom, damp wood, clay, iron\nSPICY: ginger, cinnamon, cardamom, black pepper, clove\nMARINE: seaweed, ocean air, kelp, fresh fish (in very delicate whites)\nMILKY / CREAMY: butter, cream, milk powder, dairy\nMALTY: malt, barley, brown sugar, Ovaltine, dark caramel\n\nNOTE ON VOCABULARY USE: These descriptors are not arbitrary. They map to specific molecular compounds that are chemically related to the source aromas. Linalool is found in both jasmine flowers and some fine oolongs. Geraniol appears in rose petals and in some Darjeelings. Pyrazines produce the toasty, roasted notes in pan-fired Chinese greens. You don't need to know the chemistry — but knowing that the vocabulary is grounded in chemistry should build your confidence that using it is not self-indulgent."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-tasting-block-06",
          "type": "image",
          "url": "PLACEHOLDER",
          "altText": "IMAGE PLACEHOLDER: A tea aroma wheel — a circular diagram showing aroma descriptors organised by category, radiating outward from a central 'tea aroma' hub. Inner ring: broad categories (floral, vegetal, fruity, toasty/nutty, earthy, smoky, spicy, marine, creamy, malty). Outer ring: specific descriptors within each category (orchid, jasmine, seaweed, roasted chestnut, forest floor, etc.). Colour-coded by category. Similar in format to the wine aroma wheel or coffee flavour wheel but with tea-specific vocabulary. A professional, reference-quality visual."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-tasting-block-07",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "STAGE 3: TASTE\n\nThis is the most information-dense stage — and the one most people do entirely by instinct. The framework asks you to slow down and parse it into distinct elements.\n\nFIRST IMPRESSION:\nThe immediate sensation at the front of the mouth in the first half-second of contact. Is it sweet? Sharp? Brisk? This is the fastest-registering part of the flavour profile.\n\nMID-PALATE BODY:\nAs the tea spreads across your tongue and fills your mouth, what weight and texture does it have? Body ranges from:\n• Light: thin, watery, almost like warm water with flavour added\n• Medium: a noticeable substance that fills the mouth without gripping it\n• Full: thick, coating, almost viscous — the texture of the tea itself is part of the experience\n\nBody is produced primarily by dissolved solids, amino acids, and pectins from the leaf. Shade-grown teas and pu-erh often have exceptional body; some white teas and very light greens have minimal body by design.\n\nASTRINGENCY VS. BITTERNESS: THE MOST IMPORTANT DISTINCTION IN STAGE 3\n\nThese are the two most commonly confused tasting terms — and confusing them produces wrong diagnoses and wrong brewing adjustments.\n\nASTRINGENCY is not a taste. It is a tactile sensation — a drying, gripping, puckering mouthfeel caused by tannins binding to the salivary proteins in your mouth and precipitating them. Think of how an unripe banana or a glass of cold-brew coffee makes the inside of your mouth feel dry and slightly rough. That is astringency. It is felt with the texture sensors in your mouth, not the taste buds.\n\nBITTERNESS is a taste. It is perceived at the back of the tongue (and throughout the palate in strong concentrations) and is caused primarily by catechins and caffeine. Think of the taste of dark chocolate at 90% cacao, or strong black coffee, or tonic water. That flavour at the back of your tongue is bitterness.\n\nBoth can result from over-extraction (Section 4 taught you this). But they are different sensory events:\n• If the cup makes your mouth feel dry and grip-y: too much astringency (tannin over-extraction — reduce steep time)\n• If the cup tastes sharp and harsh at the back of your tongue: too much bitterness (catechin/caffeine over-extraction — reduce temperature or time)\n• If both are present: you have comprehensively over-extracted.\n\nCRITICAL POINT: controlled bitterness in a well-made tea is not a flaw. Young sheng pu-erh has characteristic bitterness from its high catechin content — this is what makes it interesting, and what transforms into sweetness on the finish (hui gan). A high-quality Gyokuro has a very mild bitterness balanced by extraordinary umami. A fine 90% cacao chocolate has bitterness that enhances rather than undermines the experience. The question is always whether the bitterness is balanced — not whether it exists.\n\nUMAMI:\nIn fine shade-grown teas (especially Gyokuro and matcha), a fifth taste is distinctly present: umami — savoury, broth-like, silky, coating. This is produced by the amino acid L-theanine, which accumulates in shade-grown leaves because UV reduction slows its conversion to catechins. If you have eaten a good piece of aged Parmesan or sipped a clear chicken broth, you know umami. In Gyokuro, it is unmistakeable.\n\nTHE SLURP TECHNIQUE:\nProfessional tasters slurp their tea loudly and deliberately. This is not rudeness — it is technique. Slurping atomises the liquid into a fine mist and draws it rapidly over the back of the palate and through the nasopharynx, maximising contact with the olfactory receptors via the retronasal pathway. The result is a far richer flavour perception than sipping quietly. In a formal cupping setting, the audible slurp is the sound of someone paying serious attention to what they are tasting."
        },
        {
          "blockId": "sec-tasting-block-08",
          "type": "text",
          "content": "STAGE 4: FINISH\n\nThe finish is what remains after you swallow — and it is arguably the most diagnostic stage for quality.\n\nLENGTH:\nHow long does the flavour linger? Quality teas have long finishes — the flavour remains present and evolving for ten, twenty, thirty seconds or more after swallowing. Cheap or poorly made teas often have short, abrupt finishes — the flavour vanishes almost immediately.\n\nCHARACTER:\nDoes the finish taste the same as the mid-palate, or does it transform? Many fine teas evolve on the finish — a Darjeeling might end more floral than it began; an aged pu-erh might end sweeter than it tasted at mid-palate. Transformation on the finish is a sign of complexity.\n\nHUI GAN (回甘) — Returning Sweetness:\nThis is one of the most prized qualities in Chinese and Taiwanese tea evaluation. Hui gan is a wave of sweet, salivary sensation at the back of the throat, generated 10–30 seconds after swallowing a high-quality tea. It is caused by specific polyphenols and amino acids stimulating salivary glands and producing a distinctly sweet sensation where none was expected. If you have ever noticed that a good pu-erh or aged oolong makes your mouth water pleasantly a few seconds after you swallow — that is hui gan. It cannot be faked by adding sugar; it is a product of the tea's specific chemistry.\n\nHOU YUN (喉韻) — Throat Resonance:\nA related but distinct quality: a lingering sensation of depth and resonance in the throat, distinct from the mouth. Some describe it as a 'glow' or 'warmth' that sits in the throat for an extended period. It is considered by serious Chinese tea evaluators to be the ultimate marker of exceptional tea quality — particularly in fine oolongs and aged pu-erh. It is rarely present; when it is, it is unmistakeable.\n\nCONNECTION TO CEREMONY (SECTION 6): The finish is where ceremony's attention pays the highest dividend. Ichi-go ichi-e — the full, undivided presence that Chado demands — is exactly what the finish rewards. A hui gan that arrives 20 seconds after swallowing is invisible to a distracted drinker but vivid to an attentive one. The four-stage tasting framework and the contemplative practice of ceremony are, in this sense, complementary: the framework provides the structure; the ceremony provides the quality of attention that the structure requires to be useful."
