          "content": "READING THE CUP: CONNECTING FLAVOUR BACK TO ITS SOURCE\n\nThis is the synthesis skill — the payoff of all seven sections working together.\n\nEvery flavour observation has a source upstream in the chain:\n\nFLAVOUR → ORIGIN (BOTANY):\n• Vegetal, seaweed, umami notes → shade-grown Camellia sinensis var. sinensis; Japanese or Chinese mountain terroir; high L-theanine\n• Muscatel, apricot-stone, floral notes → Darjeeling first/second flush; high-altitude sinensis; the specific diurnal temperature swing and insect damage (jassid leafhopper) that concentrates these precursors\n• Malty, bold, brisk notes → Camellia sinensis var. assamica; Assam or Kenyan lowland growing; high theaflavin precursor content in the large leaf\n• Earthy, mineral, deep notes → Yunnan or Fujian old-growth sinensis; specific soil mineral profiles; aged leaf character\n\nFLAVOUR → PROCESSING (TEA TYPE):\n• Fresh, grassy, vegetal → minimal or zero oxidation; fixation immediately after picking (green tea)\n• Toasty, chestnut, roasted notes → pan-firing fixation method (Chinese greens)\n• Seaweed, umami, spinach → steaming fixation (Japanese greens)\n• Floral, creamy, orchid → partial oxidation, light oolong; aromatic compound development in the partial oxidation window\n• Malty, brisk, theaflavin-driven → full oxidation (black tea)\n• Earthy, smooth, forest floor → microbial fermentation/ageing (pu-erh)\n\nFLAVOUR → BREWING (PREPARATION):\n• Bitter and astringent → over-extracted; too hot, too long, or too much leaf\n• Flat, weak, watery → under-extracted; too cool, too brief, or too little leaf\n• Flat aromas → water too hot (aromatics volatilised); stale tea; poor storage\n• Chlorine or metallic off-notes → water quality\n\nFLAVOUR → QUALITY LEVEL:\nHere a critical distinction applies: expensive does not mean you will prefer it.\n\nA £200/100g first-flush Darjeeling is a masterpiece of its type: delicate, floral, muscatel, extraordinary aromatic complexity. A person who loves that style will find it transcendent. A person who prefers bold, milky breakfast tea will find it thin and unsatisfying by comparison. Neither response is wrong.\n\nPrice in tea tracks: rarity (limited harvest window, specific garden), labour intensity (hand-plucked, hand-rolled), market positioning (prestige, auction results), and chemical complexity. These are real quality markers. But quality-for-the-style is not the same as quality-for-you. A well-made £12 Assam that delivers exactly the bold, malty, milk-ready character you want is a better cup for you than a £200 Darjeeling that delivers the wrong style perfectly.\n\nThe trained taster's advantage is the ability to evaluate whether a tea is well-made within its style — not just whether they like it. These two evaluations coexist and are both valuable."
